column168: WHILE AT THE WILSON TRUCKING CORPORATION FACILITY IN NORCROSS, GEORGIA, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A TRAILER. UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS ONE LEAKING, FIFTY FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY, FORTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL ON A PALLET. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA RECOVERED ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM OF CONTAMINATED PRODUCT. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA PLACED THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM INTO A SIXTY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICE OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF ALL WASTE GENERATED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM MARIA, COVENANT. SHE ADVISED THEY HAVE A TRAILER IN SEATTLE CONTAINING A TOTE THAT WAS SHIPPED WITHOUT A LID. SHE ADVISED THE PRODUCT WAS ON THE TOTE, THE TRAILER AND THE FREIGHT. SHE NEEDS A TEM TO RESPOND AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. HMONE CALLED RMCAT. SPOKE WITH TODD BASEFOR. HE WILL RESPOND. HE ADVISED HE WAS DRIVING ON THE FREEWAY AND NEEDED TO GET OFF TO TAKE DOWN THE INFORMATION.. HE WILL CALL HMONE BACK SHORTLY. HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM TODD. HE TOOK DOWN THE INFORMATION. HMONE ADVISED COVENANT WAS FORWARDING A COPY OF THE BILL OF LADING TO HMONE. WHEN THAT IS RECEIVED, HMONE WILL TRACK DOWN AN MSDS. HE ADVISED HE SHOULD BE ONSITE IN ABOUT 15 MINUTES. HMONE CALLED MARIA WITH THE TEAM INFORMATION AND THE ETA. LEFT THE INFORMATION ON HER VOICE MAIL. HMONE ALSO REQUESTED A CLAIM NUMBER. HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM MARIA. SHE ADVISED THEIR SYSTEM IS DOWN SO SHE CAN NOT PROVIDE A CLAIM NUMBER AT THIS TIME. SHE ADVISED SHE WAS TOLD THERE ARE (2) TOTES LEAKING. ONE WITH A LOOSE LID AND ONE THAT IS MISSING A LID. HMONE FAXED THE WORK AUTHORIZATION TO RMCAT. HMONE CALLED MARIA TO SEE IF HER SYSTEM WAS UP YET. HMONE WAS LOOKING FOR THE SHIPPER INFORMATION. SHE ADVISED TO CALL THE DRIVER AND HE COULD PROVIDE THE INFORMATION. HMONE CALLED THE COVENANT DRIVER. HE WILL FAX THE BILL OF LADING TO HMONE. HE HANDED THE PHONE TO TODD BASEFOR. TODD ADVISED THE TOTES HAVE BEEN UNLOADED. HE ADVISED THEY TIGHTENED THE LID ON ONE TOTE. THE OTHER TOTE LID WAS LOOSE AND VIBRATED OFF COMPLETELY. HE WILL BE ABLE TO REPLACE THE LID. HE ADVISED ABOUT 5-GALLONS WAS LOST. HE WILL WIPE DOWN THE TOTES, TRAILER AND FREIGHT. HE ESTIMATES ABOUT 2-HOURS. HMONE CALLED TODD. HE ADVISED IT IS GOING SLOWER THAN EXPECTED. HE ADVISED THE PRODUCT IS SO CONCENTRATED IT IS MAKING IT DIFFICULT TO WIPE UP. THEY TOTES ARE COMPLETED AND SETTING ON THE DOCK. HE IS GETTING READY TO START MOPPING THE FLOOR. HE ADVISED THERE WILL PROBABLY NOT BE ANY DISPOSAL. THE WATER BEING USED HE CAN DILUTE FURTHER AND JUST POOR IT INTO A WATER OIL SEPARATOR AT THE TERMINAL. HE ADVISED HE WILL PROBABLY BE THERE FOR A COUPLE OF MORE HOURS. HMONE FAXED THE FORM DOT F 5800.1 TO COVENANT. HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM TODD. THEY ARE COMPLETE. HE ADVISED THEY WASHED THE TRAILER THE BEST THEY COULD. HE ADVISED THERE IS SOME STAINING. HE ADVISED THE PRODUCT IS ORANGE, BUT WHEN IT GETS WET, IT TURNS GREEN. HE ADVISED IF A CALL COMES IN FOR AN ANTIFREEZE SPILL IN THIS TRAILER, IT IS THE PRODUCT IN THE WOOD. IT CAN BE MOPPED CLEAN AND DILUTED WITH WATER AND DISPOSED OF. HE ADVISED THERE IS NO WASTE TO BE DISPOSED OF.

A SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A TRUCK AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 5920 COCA COLA BOULEVARD IN COLUMBIA, GEORGIA. WHILE UNLOADING WITH A FORKLIFT, A PALLET PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON FIBER DRUM  RELEASING APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF MATERIAL ONTO THE TRUCK BED. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENTS AND PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL DISPOSED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KENTUCKY.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER UNLOADING AND FORKLIFT OPERATIONS TO ENSURE NO FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE AND SCALED IN.  AFTER PAPERWORK WAS CHECKED, DRIVER WAS GIVEN OKAY TO UNLOAD.  UPON COMPLETION OF UNLOADING, DRIVER DISCONNECTED HIS HOSE FROM CUSTOMERS TANK WITHOUT SHUTTING DOWN THE CARGO TANK ALLOWING SOME VAPOR TO ESCAPE TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  PLANT EMPLOYEE ADVISED DRIVER TO USE SCRUBBER FOR BLEED DOWN OF TANK WHICH HE THEN DID AND THERE WAS NO FURTHER RELEASE.  DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELED AS TO PROPER BLEED DOWN PROCEDURES AND WARNED AGAINST FUTURE FAILURE TO FOLLOW PROCEDURES. EMPLOYEE OF NEIGHBORING PLANT WAS OUTSIDE AND BREATHED SOME OF THE VAPOR AND WAS COMPLAINING OF NOSE AND THROAT BURNING, BUT CONTINUED WORKING.

MANUEL AVALOS CALLED THE OFFICE AND SAID HE WAS AT THE CHP SCALES 101 SOUTH.  DURING A ROUTINE VEHICLE INSPECTION AN AMMONIA VAPOR LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY INSPECTOR.  THE SCALES WAS GOING TO BE CLOSED AND PEOPLE ON SITE EVACUATED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE WERE CALLED.  I ASKED MANUEL WHERE THE LEAK WAS LOCATED AND IF THERE WAS A CLOUD OF AMMONIA.  HE TOLD ME THE LEAK WAS IN THE LIQUID PUMP AREA, THERE WAS THE SMELL OF AMMONIA BUT NO VISIBLE AMMONIA.  NOTE: ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK TRUCKS OPERATED BY LAROCHE ARE DESIGNED SO THE ONLY TIME THE INTERNAL LIQUID VALVE OR INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE ARE OPEN, IS WHEN A DELIVERY IS BEING MADE OR THE TANK TRUCK IS BEING FILLED.  THE AIR OPERATED CONTROL FOR THE PTO DRIVE CONNECTED TO THE LIQUID AMMONIA PUMP IS INTER-CONNECTED TO THE AIR OPERATED VALVES ON THE LIQUID AND VAPOR INTERNAL VALVES.  ALSO WITH A BRAKE INTER-LOCK.  WHEN THE PTO CONTROL IS IN THE ON POSITION, THE INTERNAL VALVES OPEN AND THE BRAKES ARE LOCKED.  THE ONLY WAY TO RELEASE THE BRAKES IS TO DISENGAGE THE PTO, WHICH WILL ALSO CLOSE THE LIQUID AND VAPOR INTERNAL VALVES.  IN NORMAL TRANSPORTATION THE INTERNAL VALVES ARE CLOSED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE FLYING J TRUCK STOP, OFF OF INTERSTATE 90, EXIT 122, IN BUTTE, MONTANA, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER, ALEX ESPINOSA, PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE TRAILER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE BUTTE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AND ON SCENE. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY SEVEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND EVAPORATED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  WERNER ENTERPRISES CONTACTED OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL TO PERFORM AN INVESTIGATION.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM ON THE TRAILER.  OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL, WITH A UNITED STATES CUSTOM AGENT PRESENT, PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS FORWARDED ON WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE MSDS STATED THIS BATTERY SHOULD BE REGULATED AS A BATTERY, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, UN2794.  ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT SOMEONE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SHIPMENT WERE UNSUCCESSFUL, AND THE CONSIGNEE INFORMED US THAT THEY RECEIVE SHIPMENTS TO SEND BY BOATS TO LIBERIA. WHEN THE SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN OFF THE TRAILER AT CCX IN DES PLAINES, ONLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS NOTED. THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT AS APPARENT AT THAT TIME. IT BECAME MORE PRONOUNCED AT TIME OF DELIVERY.

SHIPMENT LEFT ONDEO NALCO BUNG WAS NOT SECURE RETURNED TO ONDEO NALCO TO REPLACE BUNG.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: THE CUSTOMER UNLOADER FAILED TO CHECK TO SEE IF THE HOSE TO THE TANK WAS HOOKED UP BEFORE UNLOADING. CUSTOMER UNLOADER DID NOT FOLLOW PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES. APPROX. 300-400 GALLONS SPILLED. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CUSTOMER.

APPROX. 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. THE DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES, AND FORGOT TO CLOSE THE UNLOADING VALVE ON THE TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY PALOMA LEASE SERVICE. THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN TIME OFF OF WORK WITH COUNSELING ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: IMPROPER LOADING AND A FAILURE TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE CAUSED THE FREIGHT TO SHIFT IN TRANSIT WHICH RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT OF ONE DRUM.  THE SECOND DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE DRUM. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: IMPROPER LOADING AND A FAILURE TO BLOCK AND BRACE PROPERLY CAUSED THE FREIGHT TO SHIFT IN TRANSIT.  THE WOOD PALLET FROM OTHER FREIGHT CAUSED A PUNCTURE WHICH RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT  WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

THE SAFETY VALVE WAS FAULTY ON THE CYLINDER WHICH CAUSED A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL  LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AND DROPPING AT A REMOTE FILL. HE THOUGHT THE REMOTE FILL WENT TO THE 20,000 GALLON TANK AND ACTUALLY  WENT TO THE 12,000 GALLON TANK. THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO MISCALCULATE THE AMOUNT THE TANK WOULD HOLD. CORRECTIVE ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN TO MARK THE DROPS WITH TANK SIZE.
DRIVER/OPERATOR OVERFILLED CARGO TANK WHILE LOADING. RETRAIN DRIVER IN PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

DUE TO A MALFUNCTION IN THE PRESSURE REGULATOR, THE AIR GOING INTO THE CARGO TANK OVERPRESSURIZED CAUSING THE RUPTURE DISK TO DISINTEGRATE.  APPROXIMATELY .5-1 GALLON OF PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM THE TANK WHEN IT OVERPRESSURIZED. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BODY OF THE TRAILER(AS THE CARGO TANK IS WITHIN A VAN TRAILER); HOWEVER A SMALL AMOUNT (< 1/2 GALLON)  MAY HAVE LEAKED FROM TRAILER DOOR.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT AS SOME PRODUCT SPRAYED THROUGH VENTS IN GOGGLES AND ENTERED EYES.  AMREX PERSONNEL WAS SENT TO THE SCENE TO FIX  VALVE AND TRANSPORT TRAILER  AND CARGO BACK TO HOME TERMINAL. CORNING FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED TO SCENE AT REQUEST OF CONSIGNEE.  THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE SITUATION BY AMREX PERSONNEL THROUGH PHONE CONFERENCE WITH CHEMTREC.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCE, REGULATOR WAS REPAIRED.  CARGO TANK REFRESHER TRAINING WAS CONDUCTED FOR ALL AMREX DRIVERS IN JUNE TO ADVISE OF OCCURRENCE AND REVIEW ALL PROPER PROCEDURES.

WHEN THE DRIVER ENGAGED THE PTO ON THE TRACTOR PUMP THE HOSE FITTING CAME LOOSE AND PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING FROM THE CONNECTION ON THE TRACTOR PUMP. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DIS-ENGAGED THE TRACTOR PUMP. THE WALNUT RIDGE FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED ON SCENE TO HELP CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PROCEDURES ON UNLOADING AND CHECKING PUMP CONNECTIONS.  THE DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT INCIDENT.

THE DRIVER HAD FINISHED UNLOADING THE CARGO TANK AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF CLEARING THE PRODUCT FROM THE UNLOADING HOSE WHEN A PLANT EMPLOYEE DISCONNECTED THE PRODUCT LINE WHILE A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS STILL IN THE LINE. ABOUT 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE END OF THE HOSE. PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND TOOK RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL.

TANKER ARRIVED TO LOAD BULK SOLVENT WASTE. SOLVENT WAS PUMPED IN FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKER TRUCK.  AS THE TANKER FILLED AND THE WASTE STORAGE TANK EMPTIED, THE TANKER BEGAN TO DRAW AIR INTO THE TRUCK. THE AIR EITHER CAUSED THE WASTE SOLVENT TO FOAM OUT THE EXHAUST OR CREATED A WAVE THAT PUSHED THROUGH THE EXHAUST.

column168: ON JUNE 26TH, 2001, 1940 HOURS A FERRELLGAS TRANSPORT WAS OFF-LOADING PROPANE AT BELCOURT OIL ON HIGHWAY 5 EAST, BELCOURT, NORTH DAKOTA 58316- OUR EMPLOYEE WAS FILLING CUSTOMER 18,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK. THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN DRIVER HAD OFF-LOADED 20% INTO STORAGE TANK. 90 GALLONS OF PROPANE WAS RELEASED FROM THE LIQUID FILL VALUE ON THE STORAGE TANK. OUR EMPLOYEE, RICHARD MCLEAN STOPPED THE DELIVERY AND CALLED SECURITY. THE BELCOURT FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND SPRAYED THE VAPOR. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FELT IT WAS SAFE TO UNHOOK THE HOSE FROM THE TRUCK AND OUR DRIVER MOVED THE TRUCK TO ANOTHER STORAGE TANK & OFF LOADED THE REMAINING PROPANE ON TRANSPORT. EMPLOYEE THEN WENT BACK AND OFF-LOADED THE 18,000 GAL STORAGE TANK. A CONTRACTOR HIRED BY. SKYDANCER CASINO, BEGAN MAKING REPAIRS TO THE LIQUID FILL VALUE ON STORAGE TANK. NO INJURIES, ROAD CLOSURES, EVACUATIONS.

column168: EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICES FOR RELEASE OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL FROM OVERTURNED SEMI TRACTOR-TRAILER AT THE US HIGHWAY 65 AND STATE HIGHWAY 163 INTERCHANGE IN PLEASANT HILL, IOWA. A SOLAR TRANSPORT TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS WEST BOUND ON 163 ATTEMPTING TO TURN SOUTHBOUND HIGHWAY 65, WHEN THE UNIT OVERTURNED, SLID ONTO THE SHOULDER AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE TRUCK WAS HAULING APPROXIMATELY 4,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND 2,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. THE ENSUING FIRE CONSUMED A MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT. AN UNDETERMINED QUANTITY OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE SURROUNDING SOIL. PLEASANT HILL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DES MOINES HAZMAT TEAMS INITIALLY PLACED ABSORBENT BOOMS DOWNSTREAM OF THE RELEASE, PREVENTING MIGRATION OF PRODUCT TO THE NEARBY CREEK. HYDRO-KLEAN RESPONDED WITH UTILITY TRUCK, EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRAILER, AND LIQUID VACUUM TRUCK. HK PERSONNEL ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND CONFERRED WITH IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES (IDNR), IOWA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (IDOT), AND SOLAR TRANSPORT OFFICIALS TO DETERMINE THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION. HK AND IDNR PERSONNEL DETERMINED THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CONTAINED BY THE ABSORBENT BOOMS AND WAS NOT A THREAT TO THE CREEK. ADDITIONAL BOOMS, PADS, AND GRANULAR MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN THE DRAINAGE AREA TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT. IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WOULD BE REMOVED TO SIGHT AND SMELL OBSERVATIONS, WITH NO ADDITIONAL SOIL SAMPLING REQUIRED. IDOT HAD ALSO EXPRESSED CONCERN ABOUT THE HEAT DAMAGE TO THE CONCRETE CULVERT, ASPHALT ROAD SHOULDER, AND THE NEARBY CHAIN LINK FENCE. THE AREA WOULD ALSO NEED TO BE RESEEDED TO IDOT RURAL MIX SPECIFICATIONS. JUNE 15, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE INCIDENT SITE TO CHECK FOR ANY CHANGE FOR ANY CHANGE IN SITE CONDITIONS. THE ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE CONTINUING TO CONTAIN ANY RESIDUAL FUEL, HOWEVER, ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE PLACED BETWEEN THE CULVERT AND THE ABSORBENT BOOMS TO COLLECT AREAS OF ISOLATED FUEL RESIDUE. JUNE 18, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN AND THEIR SUBCONTRACTORS MOBILIZED TO THE SITE TO REMOVE AND REPLACE THE CONTAMINATED AND BURNED SOIL. IDOT ENGINEER FRED THIES ALSO VISITED THE SITE AND CONFIRMED THE ASPHALT AND CULVERT WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED. MR. THIES ALSO WISHED TO HAVE THE FENCE RESTORED TO ITS PREVIOUS CONDITION WHETHER IT MEANT CLEANING OR REPLACING IT. THE DRAINAGE DITCH WAS DEWATERED PRIOR TO EXCAVATION WITH 12,220 POUNDS (^1,500 GALLONS) OF WATER HAULED TO THE DES MOINES METROPOLITAN WASTEWATER RECLAMATION FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. ALSO, APPROXIMATELY 210 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS HAULED TO THE METRO PARK EAST SANITARY LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL. DURING THE REMEDIATION PROCESS, THE DAMAGED CONCRETE CULVERT WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED PER IDOT. JUNE 20, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE WITH A HIGH PRESSURE WATER JET TRUCK TO CLEAN THE CHAIN LINK FENCE. CLEANING THE FENCE WAS SUCCESSFUL, THUS REPLACING THE AFFECTED PORTION WAS NOT REQUIRED. THE AREA WAS ALSO RESEEDED T

HK AND IDNR PERSONNEL DETERMINED THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CONTAINED BY THE ABSORBENT BOOMS AND WAS NOT A THREAT TO THE CREEK. ADDITIONAL BOOMS, PADS, AND GRANULAR MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN THE DRAINAGE AREA TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT. IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WOULD BE REMOVED TO SIGHT AND SMELL OBSERVATIONS, WITH NO ADDITIONAL SOIL SAMPLING REQUIRED. IDOT HAD ALSO EXPRESSED CONCERN ABOUT THE HEAT DAMAGE TO THE CONCRETE CULVERT, ASPHALT ROAD SHOULDER, AND THE NEARBY CHAIN LINK FENCE. THE AREA WOULD ALSO NEED TO BE RESEEDED TO IDOT RURAL MIX SPECIFICATIONS. JUNE 15, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE INCIDENT SITE TO CHECK FOR ANY CHANGE FOR ANY CHANGE IN SITE CONDITIONS. THE ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE CONTINUING TO CONTAIN ANY RESIDUAL FUEL, HOWEVER, ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE PLACED BETWEEN THE CULVERT AND THE ABSORBENT BOOMS TO COLLECT AREAS OF ISOLATED FUEL RESIDUE. JUNE 18, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN AND THEIR SUBCONTRACTORS MOBILIZED TO THE SITE TO REMOVE AND REPLACE THE CONTAMINATED AND BURNED SOIL. IDOT ENGINEER FRED THIES ALSO VISITED THE SITE AND CONFIRMED THE ASPHALT AND CULVERT WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED. MR. THIES ALSO WISHED TO HAVE THE FENCE RESTORED TO ITS PREVIOUS CONDITION WHETHER IT MEANT CLEANING OR REPLACING IT. THE DRAINAGE DITCH WAS DEWATERED PRIOR TO EXCAVATION WITH 12,220 POUNDS (^1,500 GALLONS) OF WATER HAULED TO THE DES MOINES METROPOLITAN WASTEWATER RECLAMATION FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. ALSO, APPROXIMATELY 210 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS HAULED TO THE METRO PARK EAST SANITARY LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL. DURING THE REMEDIATION PROCESS, THE DAMAGED CONCRETE CULVERT WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED PER IDOT. JUNE 20, 2002 HYDRO-KLEAN PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE WITH A HIGH PRESSURE WATER JET TRUCK TO CLEAN THE CHAIN LINK FENCE. CLEANING THE FENCE WAS SUCCESSFUL, THUS REPLACING THE AFFECTED PORTION WAS NOT REQUIRED. THE AREA WAS ALSO RESEEDED T

ACFX12055 WAS PLACED IN THE CAR SHOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BARR YARD FOR BRAKE REPAIRS. WHILE IN THE SHIP, HIGH ODOR CONTENT WAS DETECTED. THE CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHOP AND INSPECTED FOR LEAKS. NO VISIBLE LEAKS WERE SEEN; HOWEVER THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ROD SPUN FREELY, INDICATING IT WAS DEFECTIVE. THE SHIPPER OBTAINED A MOVEMENT AUTHORITY (FRA 0206132) FOR THE DEFICIENCY. WHILE AWAITING THE APPROVAL, THE CAR EMITTED MORE ODOR. ONE PERSON COMPLAINED ABOUT THE ODORS MAKING HIM ILL, BUT NO TREATMENTS WERE RENDERED. A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO PRESSURE WASH THE CAR, AND CHECK ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS. THE VAPOR VALVE PACKING, VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND THE RELIEF VALVE WERE CLEANED, CHECKED, AND TIGHTENED. THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET ROD WAS REPACKED TO ASSURE THE SEALING OFF OF ANY ADDITIONAL VAPOR EMISSION. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION ON JUNE 19, 2002

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S OPERATION CENTER REPORTED THAT THE CREW ON TRAIN Q61419 DISCOVERED TANK CAR GATX 90466, LOAD OF HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE, WAS LEAKING AND SET THE CAR OUT ON THE ENGINE TRACK IN CSXT'S HOWELL YARD IN ATLANTA, GA. CSXT MECHANICAL SUPERVISOR CHECKED CAR & DETERMINED THAT IT WAS LEAKING CONTINUOUSLY FROM THE TOP (WHILE SITTING STILL). CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR  TO STOP THE LEAK AND CONDUCT CLEANUP. THE SHIPPER, DUPONT, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE BETWEEN THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE AND THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE VALVE & WAS FLOWING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. THE PRODUCT SOLIDIFIED ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND ON THE BALLAST BENEATH THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR OPENED THE MANWAY TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR. THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS DUE TO LOOSE BOLTS ON THE EDUCTION PIPE FLANGE. THEY SECURED THE BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE FINDINGS AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO INSPECT THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR SCRAPED THE SOLIDIFIED PRODUCT OFF THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND FROM THE BALLAST BELOW THE CAR. THE SHIPPER REROUTED THE CAR BACK TO THE ORIGIN FACILITY AND ARRANGED FOR THE TWO DRUMS OF RECOVERED PRODUCT TO BE SENT THEIR ORANGE, TX FACILITY

CSXT HAZMAT MANAGERS OPENED THE PROTECTIVE COVER ON THE CAR, ADJUSTED THE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: (A-H) THERE WERE A TOTAL OF 26 SHIPMENTS ON TRAILER #280945, WHICH BURNED ON 6/19/2002  AT THE I-40 WESTBOUND REST STOP NEAR MILE MARKER #245.  THE SHIPMENTS INCLUDED SEVERAL HAZARDOUS-MATERIALS SHIPMENTS AS WELL AS OTHER GENERAL COMMODITIES. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON BOARD INCLUDED: 1 CTN. PERCHLORIC ACID 17# 1 SKD BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID 480#  1 DRM CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC 50# 1 CTN TOXIC LIQUIDS, CORROSIVE, ORGANIC 4# 1 CTN METHYL CHLOROMETHYL ETHER 4# 1 CTN BORON TRIBROMIDE 2# 1 CTN CHLOROSULFONIC ACID 2# 1 CTN HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS 6# 1 DRUM CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC 50#  OTHER COMMODITIES ON BOARD THAT MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE FIRE INCLUDE LIGNIN PITCH, WHICH IS A CELLULOSE RELATED WOODY MATERIAL AND SEVERAL SHIPMENTS OF FORMS WHICH COULD HAVE PROVIDED FUEL. INITIALLY I EXPECTED THAT THE BATTERIES PROVIDED THE SPARK TO START THE FIRE AND WAS THEREFORE, THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. HOWEVER, UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE BATTERY SHIPPER BY THE DISTRICT SAFETY MANAGER, WE FOUND THAT THE BATTERIES WERE SET IN A MOLDED CAVITY INSIDE OF A SCRUBBER. THEY WERE FURTHER SECURED BY A STICKY SUBSTANCE TO A FLAT SURFACE AND THE TERMINALS WERE PROTECTED BY PLASTIC PADS.  THEREFORE, WE ARE FAIRLY CERTAIN THAT THE BATTERIES WERE NOT THE SOURCE OF THE IGNITION.  I TALKED WITH ONE OF THE ARSON INVESTIGATORS FROM THE STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE IN OHIO AND HE INDICATED THAT IF THERE WAS ENOUGH HEAT GENERATED, ONE OF THE PIECES OF FREIGHT COULD HAVE REACHED IGNITION TEMPERATURE AND SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUSTED. SOME OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON BOARD WERE OF A NATURE THAT IF THEY CO-MINGLED WITH EACH OTHER THEY WOULD PRODUCE A CHEMICAL REACTION THAT WOULD EMANATE A GREAT DEAL OF HEAT. THEREFORE, THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE FIRE AS FAR AS WE COULD DISCERN WAS THE INITIAL CO-MINGLING OF TWO OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHICH PRODUCED A CHEMICAL REACTION. WE EXPECT THAT THE LIGNIN PITCH ACTED AS FUEL, AS IT IS CELLULOSE BASED PRODUCT WHICH IS HIGHLY FLAMMABLE, AND THERE WAS A 1200-POUND PALLET ON BOARD. ALSO, THE BORON TRIBROMIDE CAN READILY EXPLODE IF HEATED TO  A HIGH TEMPERATURE AND THE PERCHLORIC ACID IS A STRONG OXIDIZING SOLUTION.

HOWEVER, UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE BATTERY SHIPPER BY THE DISTRICT SAFETY MANAGER, WE FOUND THAT THE BATTERIES WERE SET IN A MOLDED CAVITY INSIDE OF A SCRUBBER. THEY WERE FURTHER SECURED BY A STICKY SUBSTANCE TO A FLAT SURFACE AND THE TERMINALS WERE PROTECTED BY PLASTIC PADS.  THEREFORE, WE ARE FAIRLY CERTAIN THAT THE BATTERIES WERE NOT THE SOURCE OF THE IGNITION.  I TALKED WITH ONE OF THE ARSON INVESTIGATORS FROM THE STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE IN OHIO AND HE INDICATED THAT IF THERE WAS ENOUGH HEAT GENERATED, ONE OF THE PIECES OF FREIGHT COULD HAVE REACHED IGNITION TEMPERATURE AND SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUSTED. SOME OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON BOARD WERE OF A NATURE THAT IF THEY CO-MINGLED WITH EACH OTHER THEY WOULD PRODUCE A CHEMICAL REACTION THAT WOULD EMANATE A GREAT DEAL OF HEAT. THEREFORE, THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE FIRE AS FAR AS WE COULD DISCERN WAS THE INITIAL CO-MINGLING OF TWO OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHICH PRODUCED A CHEMICAL REACTION. WE EXPECT THAT THE LIGNIN PITCH ACTED AS FUEL, AS IT IS CELLULOSE BASED PRODUCT WHICH IS HIGHLY FLAMMABLE, AND THERE WAS A 1200-POUND PALLET ON BOARD. ALSO, THE BORON TRIBROMIDE CAN READILY EXPLODE IF HEATED TO  A HIGH TEMPERATURE AND THE PERCHLORIC ACID IS A STRONG OXIDIZING SOLUTION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SIXTEEN STAINED CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SIXTEEN JUGS WERE LEAKING AND THE REMAINING FORTY-EIGHT WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY, EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE LIDS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, SUITS AND CARDBOARD.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LIDS WERE TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING JUGS AND THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING ONE HUNDRED AND SIXTY-FIVE POUND METAL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND DISSIPATED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING THE VALVE TO LOOSEN. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM TIGHTENED THE VALVE ON THE CYLINDER.  THE CYLINDER WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED ON A SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLET IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY SURROUNDING FIBERBOARD BOXES.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE SEALS ON THE PAIL LIDS TO BREAK AS A RESULT OF BEING CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL DID NOT REQUIRE ANY PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT OR OTHER CLEANUP MATERIALS. THE TWO LEAKING PAILS ON THE ORIGINAL, SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLET WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SURROUNDING FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE ALSO FORWARDED TO THAT SHIPMENT'S CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPROXIMATELY TWO CUPS OF PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE FROM AN UNKNOWN SOURCE DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING  LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO DAMAGED BAGS WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE TAPED UP AND PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

GATX 14587 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER MECHANICAL PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT SPLASHED ON TOP OF CAR WHILE CAR WAS IN THE SHOP AREA FOR UNRELATED JACKET REPAIRS. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES NOTIFIED.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT THE SPILLAGE HAD OCCURRED DURING LOADING/UNLOADING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS WASHED TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT ODOR AND HAZARD.

GATX 7473 WAS NOTED RELEASING MATERIAL FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED ONE OF FOUR FILL HOLE COVER BOLTS STOPPING THE RELEASE.  ONE CARRIER EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO PRODUCT AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY.

UTLX 30002 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT VAPOR AROUND TOP OF CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE AIR INDUCTION VALVE HAD BROKEN OFF AT THE CONNECTION TO THE CAR.  THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED AND THE CAR WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  CAR WILL MOVE UNDER FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY.

EXFU 050861 NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE TANK WAS MISSING THE TOP MANWAY COVER GASKET AND THE REAR DISCHARGE OUTLET CAP WAS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  THE GASKET WAS APPLIED AND THE CAP PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

RESIDUE CAR RCRX 1457 WAS NOTED WITH PRODUCT VAPOR AROUND TOP OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND FOUND 75 POUND PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE DEFECTIVE ALLOWING PRODUCT VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A 165 PSI RATED VALVE STOPPING THE RELEASE.

UTLX 12537 RESIDUE CAR, WAS NOTED WITH PRODUCT VAPORS COMING FROM TOP OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, REACT, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WHICH HAD BROKEN OFF THE BASE AND WAS HANGING FROM THE SECUREMENT CHAIN.  THE NEW VALVE STOPPED THE RELEASE.

ON 06/07/02 LADING WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CENTER OF TANK CAR TCIX 2058 WHILE IN THE CN/IC MAYS YARD.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE LEAK COMING FROM THE SUMP AREA.  TANK CAR ISOLATED, ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER TRANSFERRED LADING INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR FOR MOVEMENT. ON 06/08/02 AN EMPLOYEE REPORTED BEING EXPOSED TO LADING DURING THE INITIAL INCIDENT.  EMPLOYEE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HEALTH CENTER, TREATED AND RELEASED. INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX - 2(5+5)(O+4+5)=180.  CAUSE CODE - 0653.

7 CARTONS OF JOHNSON & JOHNSON PRODUCT WAS LOADED ON A PALLET, ONE CARTON IS LEAKING ONTO THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGING BOX.  CF CREW REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH PRODUCT RELEASED TO CONTAMINATE AREAS OTHER THAN THE CARDBOARD PACKAGING BOX.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF CONTAINER AND THE CONTAMINATED PACKAGING BOX WERE BOTH PLACED INTO A 25 GALLON POLY DISPOSAL DRUM BY CF EMPLOYEES.  NO WASTE REMOVAL WAS REQUESTED BY CF PERSONNEL AT THIS TIME.

WHEN THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE DRUM, A CF OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE DRUM OVER.  LESS THAT .5 GALLON WAS RELEASED.  THE ADHESIVE DRIED ON A PIECE OF CARDBOARD AND WAS THROWN AWAY.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY AND IT WAS TRANSPORTED TO PCI FOR DISPOSAL.

AREA IMMEDIATELY CORDONED BY WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR,  DARRYL CLARK.  HE ADVISED ME.  I CALLED 911.  HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED IN LESS THAN 5 MINUTES.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO PICK UP SPILL.  AREA REMAINED BLOCKED OFF FOR SEVERAL HOURS WAITING FOR SAFETY KLEEN TO ARRIVE AND COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  HAZMAT TEAM FROM WAYNE COUNTY CAUTIONED NWA CARGO TO KEEP MOTORIZED EQUIPMENT AWAY FROM SPILL AREA DUE TO FUMES THAT COULD IGNITE.  NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AS WELL.  DISCUSSED SAFETY ISSUES WITH EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.

THE TANK CAR HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED, AND THE LOADING VALVE OPENED WHILE IN TRANSPORTATION. THERE WERE NO INJURES OR EXPOSURES, AND THE CAR WAS REPAIRED AT 0251 HOURS.

THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1700 FOR RESPOND AND REPAIR. EMERGENCY RESPONDER FOR KCS MOBILIZED AT 1705 TO MONITOR FOR KCS. THE SHIPPER REPAIRED THE VALVE AT 2000. KCS REQUIRED THE SHIPPER TO RE-INSPECT THE ENTIRE CAR AND WRENCH TIGHTEN ALL FITTINGS AND SECUREMENTS. THE CAR WAS TO BE RELEASED UPON RE-CERTIFICATION INDICATING CAR IS SECURED AND GOOD FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.

THIS BOX WAS NOT VISIBLE TO THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR AND HE DID NOT KNOW HE DID THIS DAMAGE UNTIL THE PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING. THE DAMAGED BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED WITH VERMICULITE.

THE SHIPMENTS WERE BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT AND RELOAD WHEN THE ACTION LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURRED. THE ITEMS WERE DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS CAUSED BOTH INNER AND OUTER UNITS TO BREAK OPEN ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILLS WERE CONTAINED AND THE ITEMS WERE PLACED INTO  SALVAGE DRUMS. THE SHIPMENTS WERE HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THIS WAS A HEAVY WEIGHT SHIPMENT ON A PALLET INSIDE A CONTAINER. THE FREIGHT WAS OFF LOADED IN DENVER FROM LOS ANGELES AND SAT ON THE RAMP DURING THE DAY. WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED THAT EVENING IN THE AIRCRAFT THEY NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM IT. AS THEY COULDN'T TELL WHERE THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM THEY REMOVED THE ENTIRE CONTAINER AND AS THEY STARTED REMOVING FREIGHT IT STARTED SMOKING AND THEN CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED WITH A PORTABLE EXTINGUISHER AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. I'VE TALKED WITH THE SHIPPER WHO PROVIDED MSDS'S FOR THE TWO DIFFERENT CHEMICALS IN THE PACKAGES. THEY ARE BY TRADE NAME EKO-BLUE AND EKO-ORANGE AND ARE USED IN POOLS AND SPAS. THEY JUST STARTED SHIPPING THEM TOGETHER IN THE SAME BOX AND HAD NO PROBLEMS UNTIL THIS ONE. ALONG WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THE FAA/TSA WAS NOTIFIED AND A LOCAL VENDOR WAS CALLED FOR DISPOSAL AND CLEANUP.

column168: ON MONDAY, 6/17/02, AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS THE NORTH BOUND UNION PACIFIC TRAIN, MLIFW-17, DERAILED 21 CARS OF ITS CONSIST. INCLUDED AMONG THE DERAILED CARS WAS TANK CAR UTLX 67554, REPORTEDLY LOADED WITH 20,084 GALLONS OF ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS LIQUID, N.O.S. THE DERAILMENT CAUSED THE TANK CAR TO LOOSE ITS TRUCKS AND SLIDE A SHORT DISTANCE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. THIS MOTION SHEARED OFF THE EXTERNAL PORTION OF THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE NOZZLE AND THE OPERATING HANDLE. APPARENTLY, THIS ALSO ROTATED THE OPERATING HANDLE STEM TO THE OPEN POSITION.  THE TANK CAR CAME TO REST IN A SLIGHTLY NOSE DOWN POSITION ROTATING CLOCKWISE WITH THE MANWAY AT ABOUT THE 2 O'CLOCK POSITION. AN ESTIMATED 18.234 GALLONS OF THE LOAD WAS SPILLED INTO THE BALLAST AND SOIL TO THE EAST OF THE MAINLINE TRACK AND WEST OF LA HWY.1.

THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CAN TO BE CRUSHED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND ALL TWELVE CANS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG ON THE DRUM. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CREW IN CHARGE OF THE MATERIAL AT THE TIME WAS IN VIOLATION OF OUR COMPANY POLICY STATING THE ALL OF OUR MATERIALS ARE TO BE TRANSPORTED IN A SECURE ENCLOSURE UNDER LOCK AND KEY. THE REST OF THE FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: THE CARRIER FOUND THE TOTE ON THE PICK-UP TRAILER, DAMAGED. THE SHIPPER LOADED THE TOTE ONTO THE TRAILER AND JAMMED IT AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT. WHEN THIS HAPPENED, THE DISCHARGE VALVE CRACKED AND PRODUCT STARTED TO SLOWLY LEAK FROM THE TOTE. THE CARRIER DOCK OFF-LOADED THE TOTE AND PLACED IT ONTO A TOTE RECOVERY POOL. A SPILL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED OUT TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE INTO ANOTHER NEW TOTE, IN ORDER FOR THE CARRIER TO DELIVER IT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE SPILLED PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS NEUTRALIZED BY APPLYING BAKING SODA. THE TOTE WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

CARRIER'S DRIVER REPORTS THAT DRIVERS ARE NOT PERMITTED ON THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK DURING LOADING AND UNLOADING OF THEIR VEHICLES. DURING UNLOADING A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CONSIGNEE ADVISED THE DRIVER THAT THERE A DRUM ON HIS TRAILER THAT WAS LEAKING. THE DRIVER REPORTED THE SITUATION TO THE CARRIER BUT STATED THAT HE DID NOT KNOW WHAT WAS LEAKING. IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT THE LEAKING DRUM HAD BEEN FORKED BY THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADER. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN LOST. THE SPILLED MATERIAL RAN OVER A LARGE PORTION OF THE TRAILER FLOOR AND OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE CONSIGNEE RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION. THE CONTRACTOR'S CREW UNLOADED THE ENTIRE TRAILER AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR AS WELL AS THE PALLETS CONTAINING OTHER FREIGHT. UPON COMPLETION OF THE WORK IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS STILL CONTAMINATED, SO THEY CLEANED IT AGAIN. EVEN AFTER A SECOND CLEANING THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS DETERMINED TO STILL BE CONTAMINATED, SO THE CARRIER DISPATCHED ANOTHER TRAILER TO THE SITE TO RECOVER THE FREIGHT DESTINED FOR OTHER CONSIGNEES. THE FREIGHT WAS TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR INSPECTION, AND ALL SHIPPERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. AFTER BEING SURVEYED AND FOUND NOT TO BE CONTAMINATED, THE OTHER FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED TO IT'S RESPECTIVE CONSIGNEES WIHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.   THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER WAS TAKEN EMPTY TO A TRAILER CLEANING FACILITY FOR ADDITIONAL DECONTAMINATION WORK.CONSIGNEE CHEMRON CORP. ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE INCIDENT AND ITS COSTS. THEY MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO NRC, EPA AND COGNIZANT STATE AGENCIES.

CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS AT A CARTAGE COMPANY'S FACILITY TO DROP OFF SOME FREIGHT. WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR HE ENCOUNTERED AND OVERPOWERING ODOR. AFTER THE ODOR DISSIPATED, FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO UNLOAD THE FREIGHT THAT WAS TO BE LEFT THERE. AT THAT POINT THEY FOUND AN I B C WITH LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE AREA OF ITS MANWAY COVER. THEY DID NOT UNLOAD IT BUT HAD THE DRIVER MOVE TO A REMOTE AREA OF THEIR PARKING LOT. CARRIER RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPERVISOR INSPECTED THE PACKAGE AND DETERMINED THAT A GASKET THAT SEALS ITS FILL PORT HAD BEEN CUT. THE SUPERVISOR ACQUIRED AND REPLACED THE GASKET. CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL CLEANED THE EXTERIOR OF THE PACKAGE AND ALLOWED THE VEHICLE TO CONTINUE ON ITS WAY.

THIS IS MATERIAL BEING RETURNED TO ITS ORIGINAL SHIPPER. PAILS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN HIGHLY STACKED ON THEIR PALLETS BY THE SHIPPER (ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE). ENROUTES, ONE OR MORE PAILS WERE CRUSHED AND BEGAN LEAKING, DUE TO THE WEIGHT ON THEM. THE DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. HE WAS VERY CLOSE TO THE CONSIGNEE'S (ORIGINAL SHIPPER) LOCATION AND SATISFIED THAT NO ESCAPE FROM THE TRAILER WAS LIKELY, SO HE CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THEY ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT. DURING UNLOADING, ONE ADDITIONAL PAIL WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING SLOWLY.

column168: THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE FITTING (THE RESULT OF CONSTRUCTION ON NEW PIPING).  WHEN A TANKER TRUCK UNLOADED INTO THE NEW PIPING, THE LOOSE FITTING CAME APART, CREATING THE DISCHARGE OF 1,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL ONTO THE PROPERTY.  THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE LOADING RACK AREA TO THE OIL WATER SEPARATOR AREA AND LEFT THE PROPERTY AT THAT POINT; ENTERING THE TOE RIVER.  THE DRIVER OF THE TANKER REALIZED WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND CEASED PUMPING AND ALERTED THE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT TEAM.  OF THE 1000 GALLONS, 400 WAS CONTAINED IN THE SPILL CONTAINMENT AREA AND APPROXIMATELY 422 GALLONS WAS DISCHARGED INTO THE NORTH TOE RIVER.  THE BALANCE OF PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE SOIL ON THE PROPERTY WHICH WAS EVACUATED IMMEDIATELY AND REMOVED.  THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR (NEO) WAS NOTIFIED AND CONDUCTED ON-SITE CLEAN-UP BY USE OF BOOMS AND SORBANT IN THE RIVER.  NEO FLOATED THE RIVER TO ENSURE THAT NO PRODUCT WAS LEFT ON THE BANKS OR IN THE WATER. FEDERAL AND STATE WILDLIFE AUTHORITIES MONITORED THE RIVER AS WELL.  THE DURATION OF THE CLEAN-UP WAS TWO DAYS.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: ADDITIONAL CONTAINMENT WALLS WERE BUILT, THE OLD LOADING RACK HAS BEEN DISCONTINUED, A NEW SPILL PLAN HAS BEEN WRITTEN AND STAFF HAS HAD REFRESHER TRAINING.

BULK TRANSPORTATION DRIVER WAS DELIVERING SODIUM HYPOCHORITE SOLUTION TO CONSIGNEE STORAGE TANK VIA BULK'S TWO-INCH CARGO HOSE PERMANENTLY ATTACHED TO CARGO TANK. OTHER END OF CARGO HOSE IS CONSTRUCTED WITH TWO-INCH, FOUR-BOLT FLANGE OF PVC CONSTRUCTIONS. CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING LINE IS TWO-INCH POPLYPROPYLENE CAMLOCK FITTING. DRIVER HAD TO ATTACH A FLANGE TO CAMLOCK ADAPTER IN ORDER TO MAKE A CONNECTION. PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY PRESSURIZING THE CARGO TANK WITH COMPRESSED AIR. DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER, A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE CONSIGEE'S CAMLOCK CONNECTION. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO FIXE THE LEAK DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER, WHICH RESULTED IN A COMPLETE FAILURE OF THE CONNECTION. EMERGENCY SHUTOFF ON CARGO TANK WAS ACTIVATED, PRODUCT LOSS WAS ESTIMATED AT 200 GALLONS. PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO PAVEMENT AND CAUSED AN EYE INJURY TO DRIVER DUE TO FAILURE TO WEAR PRESCRIBED PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE SINCE IT REMAINED ON THEIR PROPERTY. BULK TRANSPORTATION'S POLICY PROHIBITS OUR DRIVERS FROM ENGAGING IN ANY REPAIR ACTIVITIES INVOLVING SHIPPER AND/OR CONSIGNEE'S EQUIPMENT. POLICY IS REINFORCED THROUGH PROGRESSIVE DISCIPLINARY ACTION AND AWARENESS AT DRIVER SAFETY MEETING AND TRAINING.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Hose; Loading or Unloading Lines; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON JUNE 3, 2002 (6/3/02) MONKE BROS. FERTILIZER CO. WAS REFILLING THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INVENTORY FOLLOWING THE 2002 PLANTING SEASON.  AT 0900 THE TRANSFER HOSE BURST DURING THE REFILLING PROCESS.  THE HOSE DID NOT PERFORM AS SPECIFIED AND DID NOT CLOSE OFF THE SUPPLY HOOKUP VALVE.  THE SMART HOSE SYSTEM WAS DESIGNED TO DETECT ANY LEAKS IN THE HOSE.  IF ANY LEASKS WERE DETECTED THE SMART HOSE IS DESIGNED TO IMMEDIATELY CLOSE VALVES IN BOTH SUPPLY & RECEIVING HOOKUPS, THUS STOPPING FLOW IN BOTH DIRECTIONS. APPROXIMATELY 30,000 LBS. OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DOUSED THE VAPOR WITH WATER AND SHUT OFF THE VALVE IN THE SUPPLY TRUCK.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: 1.  DURING THE FIRST WEEK OF JULY 2002, A RESPONSE EFFORT WAS MADE TO LEAKING IM TANK GESU8008527 ON THE MSC VERONIQUE AT THE MAHER TERMINAL IN NEW JERSEY.  RESPONSE EFFORTS ENDED WITH THE SUCCESSFUL OFFLOADING OF THE TANK WITH NO PERSONAL INJURIES OR FURTHER SPILLAGE.  2.  ON THURSDAY, JUNE 27, THE VESSEL'S MASTER REPORTED THAT THE CREW HAD DETECTED A SMALL LEAK FROM  AN IM TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL STOWED ON DECK ON THE STARBOARD SIDE AT ABOUT THE MIDSHIPS POINT OF THE VESSEL.  THE TANK CONTAINED THE HAZMAT UN1143, "CROTONALDEHYDE, STABILIZED", WHICH IS POISONOUS BY INHALATION AND FLAMMABLE.  THE MSC VERONIQUE WAS ENROUTE FROM SOUTH AFRICA TO THE UNITED STATES.  NEW YORK WAS THE VESSEL'S FIRST SCHEDULED U.S. PORT OF CALL AND UPON LEARNING OF THE LEAK, THE U.S. COAST GUARD PROHIBITED ENTRY TO THE PORT UNTIL ASSURANCES COULD BE GIVEN THAT THE TANK OR ATMOSPHERE AROUND IT WAS NO LONGER DANGEROUS.  3.  AFTER RECEIVING THE INITIAL REPORT FROM THE MASTER, THE DANGEROUS GOODS DEPARTMENT IN ANTWERP WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY AND CONTACT THE SHIPPER SASOL CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES TO ADVISE OF THE SITUATION AND SEEK THE SHIPPER'S ASSURANCE OF TAKING ACTION AND FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITY.  THE VESSEL'S MASTER CREW LAUNCHED THE INITIAL RESPONSE WITH GREAT RESULTS AS THEY CONTROLLED THE DISCHARGE AND CONTAINED THE SPILL.  4.  ACCORDING TO MR. DIETER EHLS WITH BOWER LIQUID TRANSPORT, SPRING, TX, AGENT FOR THE SHIPPER, THE TANK APPARENTLY HAD BEEN OVERLOADED AT THE PORT OF LOADING AND THE CARGO EXPANDED WHEN THE SHIP CROSSED THE EQUATOR AND HEADED INTO WARMER, SUMMER TEMPERATURES.  THE CARGO WAS RELEASED THROUGH A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE TANK AND DRIPPED FROM A DRAINAGE LINE ONTO THE HATCH COVER AND DECK.  BECAUSE THE CONTAINMENT BOX COVERING THE VALVES AT THE TOP OF THE TANK WAS CLOSED, THERE WAS NO WAY TO SEE IF THE VALVE HAD RESET PROPERLY OR WAS PERMANENTLY DAMAGED SO AS TO CONTINUE LEAKING.  IN ADDITION, THERE WERE OTHER HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS CARGO CONTAINERS IN THE VICINITY.  DONNING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT, THE CREW ATTACHED A HOSE TO THE END OF THE DRAIN PIPE AND LED IT INTO AN EMPTY OIL DRUM, PLACING THE HOSE INTO A BUNG HOLE AND STUFFING RAGS AROUND THE OPENING TO STOP THE VAPORS FROM SPREADING.  THE DRUM WAS LASHED IN PLACE TO PREVENT ITS MOVEMENT.  5.  THE SHIPPER IN SOUTH AFRICA ASSUMED FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE RESPONSE EFFORT ON SATURDAY, JUNE 29, AND ASKED MSC FOR RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CLEANUP CONTRACTORS.  FORTUNATELY, A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR HAD ALREADY BEEN ALERTED IN CASE THE SHIPPER DID NOT OR WOULD NOT ASSUME RESPONSIBILITY/  PETROCLEAN INC. (2 DORRINGTON RD., CARNEGIE, PENNSYLVANIA 15106) WAS CALLED IN TO RESPOND AT THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER. THEY WERE DIRECTED TO MEET THE VESSEL IN NEWARK, NJ.  THEY ARRIVED ON SCENE THE FOLLOWING TUESDAY EVENING, JULY 2, AND BOARDED THE VESSEL AT ANCHORAGE VIA SMALL BOAT.  PETROCLEAN HAD SUBCONTRACTED AN AIR-MONITORING TEAM FROM CTEH, INC. FROM ARKANSAS.  THE AI

FAULTY ON SITE EQUIPMENT - NON FUNCTIONAL ALARM SYSTEM.  DRIVER FAILED TO CONFIRM TANK LEVEL ACCURATELY.  ADDRESSED EQUIPMENT WITH BOSTON UNIVERSITY - FIRED THE DRIVER, FAILURE TO FOLLOW SOP FOR OFFLOAD - FAILURE TO CALL DISPATCH FOR ON SITE PROCEDURES.

column168: (A - F) ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 40 WEST, THE DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE RELEASING FROM THE LEAD TRAILER.  THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE REST AREA AT MILE MARKER 247. UPON INVESTIGATION, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM BOTH ENDS OF THE TRAILER AND REACTING WITH THE TRAILER'S MUD-FLAPS, CAUSING ADDITIONAL SMOKE.  THE FORREST CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  FIRST RESPONSE, INC. OF MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO PERFORM FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND CLEANUP.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS, THE LEAD TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE AND ALL CONTENTS WERE LOST.  THE REAR TRAILER ALSO CAUGHT FIRE, BUT WAS ONLY A PARTIAL LOSS.    THE LEAD TRAILER CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS: TOXIC LIQUIDS, CORROSIVE, ORGANIC, N.O.S.; CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S.; HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS; PERCHLORIC ACID; METHYL CHLOROMETHYL ETHER; BORON TRIBROMIDE AND BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID.  THE REAR TRAILER CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL: FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE FIRE IN THE LEAD TRAILER WAS DUE TO A CHEMICAL REACTION, AS A RESULT OF A BREACH OF PACKAGING.  THE MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THIS PACKAGING FAILURE IS UNDETERMINED.  A NEARBY STREAM WAS IMPACTED.  THE REST AREA AND A LOCAL APARTMENT COMPLEX WERE EVACUATED. ALL PREGNANT WOMEN AT THE BAPTIST MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN FORREST CITY WERE EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. THE MSDS WERE REQUESTED.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON I-244 AND EXITED ONTO THE LOOP TO US412 W.  THE LOOP IS MARKED AT 25 MPH AND THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 35 MPH WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS UNIT AND IT OVERTURNED ON US 412.  THE TANK WAS PUNCTURED AND A RELEASE OF 5,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED ONTO THE HIGHWAY AND INTO A SEWER THAT EMPTIES INTO THE ARKANSAS RIVER.  SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICE AND THE TULSA FIRE DEPT WERE ONSITE TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE GASOLINE.  SEWER LINES WERE FLUSHED WITH WATER AND BOOMS WERE SET UP AT THE OUTLETS TO COLLECT THE GASOLINE. column168: DRIVER PULLED INTO GOODYEAR WITH LOADED TRAILER WHEN LAPORTE, TX POLICE PULLED UP TO INDICATE THAT THERE WAS A SMELL COMING FROM THE TRAILER. DRIVER AND TRAILER WERE INSIDE THE GATES OF GOODYEAR.  GOODYEAR AND MYSELF LOOKED AT THE TRAILER AND NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS AROUND THE 407 VALVE. SOME PRODUCT WAS IN THE CRASH BOX (ABOUT 1/4 "- 1/2").  A SLOW DRIP WAS COMING FROM THE OVERFLOW TUBES IN TRAILER.  GOODYEAR PUT FLOOR DRY DOWN TO ABSORB.  GOODYEAR INDICATED THAT WE COULD PARK TRAILER AT THEIR SITE WHILE MCKENZIE GETS ANOTHER VALVE TO REPLACE. RANDY HARRELL ARRIVED AT GOODYEAR AND REPLACED THE 407 VALVE WITH A NEW ONE.  AFTER DOING SO HE HAD DRIVER PULL FORWARD TO ENSURE THAT THERE WERE NO LEAKS.  THE DRIVER DID SO AND RANDY NOTICED THAT THERE WAS STILL A LEAK.  THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE DOME LID AND GETTING ON THE 407 VALVE.  RANDY OPENED THE DOME LID AND THERE WAS A SAMPLE TOOL THAT THE LOADER APPARENTLY HAD LEFT HOOKED TO THE DOME.  CLOSED THE DOME AND TIGHTENED.  TOOL COULD NOT BE SEEN WITHOUT OPENING DOMELID.  TOOL WAS TAKEN OUT AND BROUGHT TO SHOP.  DOME LID WAS SHUT AND TIGHTENED.  DRIVER UNLOADED TRAILER WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

column168: AFTER LOADING FLIGHT 1431, THE FLEET SERVICE CLERK NOTICED AN ACETONE TYPE SMELL.  A SMALL CARRY-ON SIZE SOFT-SIDED GRAY AND BLACK COSMETIC BAG WITH A WET SPOT ON THE SIDE WAS IDENTIFIED AS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE CUSTOMER SERVICE MANAGER TRACED THE BAG TO A PASSENGER ON THE FLIGHT AND HAD THE PASSENGER IDENTIFY THE CONTENT AS AN ACRYLIC NAIL TECHNICIAN PRODUCT -  TAMMY TAYLOR NAIL LIQUID.  A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF THE LIQUID LEAKED OUT OF THE 8-OZ PLASTIC SCREW TOP BOTTLE - LESS THAN ONE OUNCE. ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THE SPILL REACHED THE FLOOR OF THE BELLY; AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL CHECKED AND CLEARED THE MIDDLE BELLY.  TSA AGENT ADVISED WE DID NOT NEED TO SEND THEM A REPORT BECAUSE THESE ITEMS FELL UNDER THE PERSONAL TOILETRY EXEMPTION.  THE PASSENGER WAS EDUCATED ABOUT THE HAZARDS OF UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ON AIRCRAFT AND ASKED TO ENSURE BOTTLES ARE PROTECTED FROM LEAKING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE SHIPPING VESSEL (CTI VAN 7027) A 48' ENCLOSED VAN, WAS RECEIVED FROM THE MEXICAN TRANSPORTER ECOTRANSPORTES INTERNACIONALES, S.A. DE C.V. ON THE EVENING OF JUNE 7, 2002. A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT WAS PERFORMED BY THE CT FACILITY MANAGER (MR. JEFF CLARK) PRIOR TO ACCEPTING THE SHIPMENT INTO CT CUSTODY AT 400 INGLEWOOD DR, EL PASO, TX. THE VAN WAS PARKED IN A STAGING AREA BY THE MEXICAN TRANSPORTER AND CT ACCEPTED THE LOAD. ON JUNE 8, 2002 A SECURITY GUARD NOTICED A SMALL DRIP FROM THE REAR OF THE VAN, AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE EL PASO,TX FIRE DEPARTMENT (FD). THE EL PASO FD ERT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND PERFORMED THE INITIAL PREVENTIVE ACTIONS. AT APPROXIMATELY 0740 THE FD RELEASED THE INCIDENT TO CT, WHO MOBILIZED AN ERT TEAM TO REMEDIATE THE RELEASE. THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS WERE TAKEN BY CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION TO REMEDIATE THE INCIDENT. 1) ABSORPTION OF ALL RELEASED LIQUIDS FROM THE ASPHALT. 2) REMOVAL OF ALL CONTAINERS FROM THE SHIPPING VESSEL. 3) OVER PACKAGING OF (3) DAMAGED DRUMS AND (1) LEAKING DRUM. 4) REMOVAL OF APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF EXCESS FLUIDS FROM THE OVEFILL ORIGINAL 92 DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT. 5) DECONTAMINATION OF THE VAN, DRUMS, AND ASPHALT, THESE ACTIONS GENERATED (1) DRUM WITH ABSORBENTS, PPE, MOP HEADS AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF DIRT. 6) RELOADING OF THE SHIPMENT CONTAINERS INTO THE VAN FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE DESIGNATED TSDF. 7) THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION WAS NOTIFIED AND INSPECTED THE LOCATION AT 1430 ON JUNE 8, 2002. 8) THE US COASTGUARD/NATIONAL SPILL RESPONSE CENTER WA NOTIFIED OF A R.Q. RELEASE AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 ON JUNE 8, 2002.

column168: AT 2219 HOURS ON JUNE 6, 2002 TANK CAR RCRX1355 WAS FOUND BY CSXT YARD CONDUCTOR LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN THE HAMLET CLASSIFICATION YARD. CSXT MANAGERS IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATION'S TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE ACCORDING TO THE REGULATIONS.  THE SHIPPER - REAGENT CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED, DIRECTOR OF TRANSPORTATION DAVID STEWART, WAS THE POINT OF CONTACT.  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL, CHARLOTTE, NC LOCATION RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF CSXT AND REAGENT.  THE INVESTIGATION REVEALED PRODUCT DRIPPING AT A STEADY RATE FROM AROUND THE SUMP AREA.  THE ACTUAL LOCATION OF THE BREACH WAS ABLE TO BE DETERMINED.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TANK CAR RCRX1355 INTO RCRX1460.  APPROXIMATELY 155 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM TANK CAR.  RCRX1355 WAS CLEANED AND PURGED ON JUNE 10, 2002. REAGENT WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR REQUESTING FRA APPROVAL TO MOVE A CONFORMING TANK CAR TO RESCAR INDUSTRIES IN ORANGE, TEXAS TO INVESTIGATE ROOT CAUSE OF LINER FAILURE.

CSX TRANSPORTATION CONDUCTOR WORKING IN RUSSELL YARD REPORTS BEING LIGHTLY SPRAYED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM T/C GATX-6794.  CSXT MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATIONS TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE CONTAMINATED EMPLOYEE WASHED THE EFFECTED AREAS WITH WATER AND REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM A LOCAL HOSPITAL WITH NO PRESCRIPTIONS ISSUED (NON-FRA PERSONAL INJURY). INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE IMMEDIATE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE BLOWN 165 POUND FLANGIBLE DISC.  OTHER FACTORS CONTRIBUTING TO THE RELEASE WAS A BROKEN/MISSING FLANGIBLE DISC SURGE PROTECTOR AND BROKEN FLANGIBLE DISC INSPECTION PLUG.  IN ADDITION 4 OF 4 QUICK OPENING FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE FOUND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND VAPOR VALVE PACKING RETAINER WAS LOOSE.  PETROCLEAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS RESCAR ARE SCHEDULED TO MAKE THE REQUIRED REPAIRS THAT ALLOW THE CAR TO BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  NORFALCO SALES REP., DON GRENVILLE, WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE NON-ACCIDENTAL RELEASE FINDINGS.  RUSSELL YARD MANAGEMENT IS INVESTIGATING THE OPERATING PRACTICES ASSOCIATED WITH SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND THE RELEASE.

column168: FILE:2214 F & D, SHIPPER: E & R INDUSTRIAL SALES, AWB# TRY 87695107366 BUF. ON 06/05/2002 A CALL CAME IN AT 00:59 THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN SECONDARY 9 BUILDING "D" OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND TERRY RUGGERIE RESPONDED. EMPLOYEES WERE MOVED OUT OF THE AREA UNTIL IT WAS RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN. UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN INVESTIGATING THE SHIPMENT TO DETERMINE WHAT THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DID NOT SEE ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTERMOST PACKAGING TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THERE WASN'T A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. THE TECHNICIANS ONLY FOUND AN AIR WAYBIL ATTACHED TO THE PACKAGE, BUT IT DID NOT INDICATE WHAT THE CONTENTS WERE. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OBSERVED THAT  A 1 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD COME OUT OF THE PACKAGE DUE THE LEAKAGE WHICH WEAKENED ONE END OF THE PACKAGE. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE AND DISCOVERED 3 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE RECEPTACLES IDENTICAL TO THE ONE THAT HAD SEPARATED FROM THE PACKAGE. THE 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS DUE TO THE LID COMING COMPLETELY OFF THE RECEPTACLE. THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED WITH ABSORBENT AND PUT INTO A UNSPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED INTO THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA/TSA INVESTIGATION. CLEAR OF SCENE: 01:20

E.M.I. JOB # 16676: DRIVER HAD PULLED INTO AN EMPTY LOT NEXT TO PILOT TRUCK STOP AT EXIT 148 INTERSTATE HWY 10 (WESTBOUND) IN VAN HORN, TEXAS.  DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM NOSE OF TRAILER (#714), IMPACTED AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 FEET IN DIAMETER, THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS DISPATCH AND ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND WAS REQUESTED TO COORDINATE THE RESPONSE TO THE RELEASE.  DOT-LINE REPORTED THE RELEASE TO THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY.  THE DRIVER HAD ALSO NOTIFIED THE CLUBERSON COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED TIMMONS CONSTRUCTION COMPANY TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  AUTHORITIES HAD EVACUATED THE PILOT TRUCK STOP.  THE RESPONSE TEAM MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED.  THE PALLETIZED 5-GALLON CONTAINERS HAD SLIPPED OFF THE PALLET AND WERE CRUSHED.  11 OF THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED/CRUSHED AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE SHRINK-WRAPPED BUT WERE NOT SHRINK-WRAPPED TO THE PALLETS THEMSELVES.  AS THE LOAD SHIFTED THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS SLID OFF THE PALLETS.  THE RESPONSE TEAM BEGAN CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  17 OF THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE IN NON-SHIPABLE CONDITION.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO 55-GALLON OPEN-TOP DRUMS.  ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS ALSO GENERATED. THESE DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO TIMMONS' FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS.

column168: CONTAINER NUMBER MSKU2100621 20FT STEEL CONTAINER SAID TO CONTAIN 78-65 GALLON DRUMS. HURRICANE TRUCKING ARRIVED TO PULL MSKU2100621 AT 1352 AND REPORTED LEAK IN ROW 51524. PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AT 1410 AND ARRIVED ON SCENE 1415. PRODUCT ALKYL SULFONIC ACID DETERMINED TO BE LEAKING APPX. 3-5 GALLONS ON THE CEMENT GROUND. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT IN THE WATER. AREA WAS SECURED TO PREVENT ALL THROUGH TRAFFIC. EMERGENCY RESPONSE VENDOR HULCHER SERVICES NOTIFIED FOR CLEAN-UP. HURRICANE TRUCKING NOTIFIED CONSIGNEE BARRY REICHENBERG OF AMERICAN METALS & CHEMICAL CORP. (954-570-8334) THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. MR. REICHENBER CALLED AND FAXED MSDS TO HOUTRM/MC WHICH WAS DISTRIBUTED TO PORT OF HOUSTON FD AND HULCHER. NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER NOTIFIED 1450 WITH REPORT NUMBER 613968. DOORS WERE OPENED BUT PRODUCT APPEARED TO NOT BE LEAKING FROM REAR DRUMS AND CURRENTLY  UNDETERMINED HOW MANY DRUMS ARE AFFECTED. TOP TIER OF DRUMS ARE ON PALLETS AND SHRINK-WRAPPED. BOTTOM TIER IS NOT ON PALLETS, NOT SHRINK-WRAPPED AND NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS OBSERVED. CONTAINER HAD TO BE MOVED TO ANOTHER LOCATION WHERE IT COULD BE UNLOADED AND CLEANED AND ISOLATED. BOOMS PLACED INSIDE DOORS TO PREVENT LEAK AND CHASSIS AND CONTAINER CLEANED PRIOR TO MOVEMENT.MSKU2100621 PULLED BY YARD TRUCK TO RAILHEAD DOCK. LITTER PLACED INSIDE DOORS ON TOP OF AND AROUND BOOMS TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT FROM LEAKING AND SECURED FOR THE NIGHT. HULCHER CLEANED LOCATION 51524 AND PUT CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN 2 DRUMS. RAIN WAS FORECASTED FOR NEXT THREE DAYS, HULCHER MADE LIKE A DIAPER FOR THE CONTAINER USING WITH PLASTIC WRAP UNDER AND AROUND THE BOTTOM AND REAR OF THE CONTAINER. GRANULATED ABSORBENT WAS PLACED INSIDE THE PLASTIC WRAP TO FORM A DIKE AND SODA ASH WAS SCATTERED WITHIN THE DIKE. CONTAINER WAS MONITORED THROUGHOUT THE WEEKEND BY MANAGEMENT AND HULCHER PERSONNEL. NO CLEAN-UP ACTION WAS NEEDED DURING THE WEEKEND. SURVEYORS WERE SENT IN ON MONDAY 7/01/02 TO BE PRESENT DURING THE FINAL CLEANUP BY HULCHER. HULCHER REMOVED 2 PALLETS OF FOUR DRUMS, EACH OFF THE TOP TIER BY THE BACK DOOR, THEN REMOVED SEVEN SINGLE DRUMS, THAT HAD BEEN HAND STOWED ON THE BOTTOM TIER. THE DRUM ON THE FAR LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER BY THE BACK DOOR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. APPEARED ONE OF THE BUNG HOLES DID NOT HAVE A CAP SEAL AND WAS CRACKED, THUS AIR WAS ABLE TO GET INTO THE DRUM. THE PRESSURE FROM THE AIR FORCED THE PRODUCT THRU THE PINHOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THERE WAS NO NAILS OR PUNCTURES IN THE DRUM. THE PINHOLE WAS ABOUT THE SIZE OF THE END OF A FOUNTAIN PEN. IT WAS DETERMINED THE PACKAGE FAILED. THE MARKING ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS ZOHAR DETERGENT FACTORY, 18239, K BUTZ, DALLA ISRAEL PHONE 927-498-7234,LABS 100/W, UN 2586, IMO8. UN PACKAGING MARKS: GREIF BRO. CORPORATION, INDUSTRIAL SUPPLY CONTAINER GROUP, UN 1H1/Y12/100/01/USA/MS174,P653,246L,2.2MM, 65 US GALLON. ANOTHER MARKING ON THE DRUMS, LABS W220,NW220KG, DATE 05/05/02, GROSS WEIGHT 230KGS, PRODUCT OF ISRAEL, IMO 8. PRODU

column168: A PRODUCT THAT HAS A HAZMAT LABEL FLAMMABLE SOLID 4.1 HAS BEEN RELEASED. THE PRODUCT IS LOCATED IN HE REAR OF TRAILER NUMBER 7635. CF PERSONNEL CLOSED THE TRAILER DUE TO THE HAZARDOUS ASSOCIATED WITH THE PRODUCT. MR.KYLE BLAZE STATED THERE ONLY APPEARS TO BE A SMALL RELEASE OF PRODUCT. MR. TUCKER CONTACTED MR BRAD BECKER OF HAZ-MAT RESPONSE AND BREIFED HIM OF THE SITUATION. MR. BECKER AND TWO TECHS WENT TO THE SITE TO REPACKAGE THE MATERIAL. MR. TUCKER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO OBTAIN AND MSDS. MR. TUCKER SENT A COPY OF THE MSDS TO THE CF TERMINAL. HE TEAM ARRIVED ONSITE AT 1400. MR. BECKER CONTACTED MR. TUCKER AND EXPLAINED THE CARGO WAS LOADED WITH A HEAVY SKID ABOVE THE FIBER KEGS. THE WOOD BETWEEN THE KEGS AND THE OTHER SKID FAILED CAUSING 7 DRUMS TO BECOME DAMAGED. TUCKER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO RETURN THE PRODUCT. THE SHIPPER AGREED TO ACCEPTED THE CARGO. THE RESPONSE WAS COMPLETED 1625HRS. NO WASTE WAS CREATED.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: TWO CARTONS WERE WET WHEN UNLOADED AT UBI. SUPERVISOR ON DUTY OPENED LEAKING CARTONS AND FOUND LEAKING SEAMS ON BAGS INSIDE. I CONTACTED JEFF TURNER, UNH SAFETY, AND NIKKI AT CHEMTREC. PER JEFF TURNER WE REMOVED THE TWO LEAKING CARTONS AND HELD THEM IN UBI HAZ-MAT AREA. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS MOVED TO DESTINATION. NIKKI AT CHEMTREC SAID THE SHIPPER WOULD CONTACT US WITH DISPOSITION OF THE LEAKING CARTONS UPON RECEIPT OF THE REPORT FROM CHEMTREC. WE HAVE NOT BEEN CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER AT THIS TIME. THERE WAS NO VISABLE DAMAGE TO THE CARTONS, OR ANY SIGN OF ROUGH HANDLING. THIS APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BE FAULTY SEAMS IN THE BAGS CONTAINING THE HAZ-MAT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DRS TIM DENNIS REPORTED FINDING THIS LEAKING HAZ-MAT WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER ENGC-10025. SUPERVISOR ON DUTY, CARL HENDRICKS CHECKED IT AND CONTACTED JEFF TURNER, CWX/UNH SAFETY. PER JEFF TURNER'S INSTRUCTIONS, I CALLED OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL FOR CLEAN UP.  THIS HAZ-MAT HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF A PALLET OF FENCE BRACKETS IN BURLAP BAGS. THE SHARP EDGES OF THE BAGS PUNCTURED THE HAZ-MAT CONTAINERS, ALLOWING IT TO LEAK DOWN INTO THE BAGS OF FENCE BRACKETS. MIKE BAKKE FROM OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL SEPARATED THE LEAKING HAZ-MAT, CONTAMINATED FENCE BRACKETS, AND PACKAGING, AND PLACED THEM INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR TRANSPORT BY OLYMPUS' VENDOR. THESE DRUMS ARE STILL IN UBI HAZ-MAT AREA, WAITING PICK UP.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO EXHIBIT AN ODOR AND BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN TWO QUARTS OF WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE A PAINT RELATED MATERIAL. THE INNER CONTAINERS SAID "FLAMMABLE". THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET LISTED A FLASH POINT OF 29 DEGREES CELCIUS. AS THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD NOT BEEN OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. FAA AGENT DENNIS KRAUSE WAS NOTIFIED. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AT THE FEDEX FACILITY PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

STEVE HAMPTON, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN ODOR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS DETECTED FROM LOADED TANKCAR GATX 93400 CURRENTLY LOCATED ON THE MAIN LINE AT THE PHOENIX YARD. DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED HE WOULD RESPOND TO PHOENIX ALONG WITH CONTRACTOR ERI. UPON ARRIVAL PHOENIX, AZ. MR JOHNSON CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF TANK CAR GATX 93400 AND FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE GASKET AREA ON THE "B" END OF THE SECURING PLATE FOR THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND FIELD REPAIRS COULD NOT BE COMPLETED DUE TO THE CAR BEING UNDER PRESSURE. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ARRANGED FOR THE CAR TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO RAIL CAR GATX 93462. THIS TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT EXCEPTION AND THE CAR PRESSURE WAS REDUCED TO 0 PSI. SHIPPER OBTAINING FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL FOR MOVEMENT OF THE CAR FROM PHOENIX, AZ TO WEST COLTON, CALIF. CARE OF GATX.

column168: LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER OF A VENTING TANKCAR AT DOLTON YARD IN CHICAGO, IL. DON KEEN, SUPERVISOR OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THAT IAPX1007, A LOAD OF REFRIGERATED ARGON, WAS REPORTED TO BE VENTING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED AIR LIQUIDE, SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE, TO HAVE THEM INSPECT THE CAR.  MAX VARNER WITH AIR LIQUIDE ADVISED THAT ONE OF THEIR TECHNICIANS WOULD CHECK THE CAR. MR. MAX VARNER WITH AIR LIQUIDE ADVISED THAT ONE OF THEIR TECHNICIANS WOULD CHECK THE CAR. MR. VARNER CALLED WITH FOLLOW-UP INFORMATION THAT THE ROAD VALVE ON THE TANK CAR WAS CLOSED AND WAS NOT ALLOWING THE CAR TO VENT NORMALLY. THE TECHNICIAN OPENED THE VALVE AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSIT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED LEAKING CONTAINER MOLU 701875, WHICH CONTAINED FIFTEEN DRUMS OF PAINT AND MIXED FAK. MR. COOPER REPORTED APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PAINT HAD LEAKED AND THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN CONTAINED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK AND ISOLATED. CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, MITSUI OSK LINES AND SPOKE WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OUT OF THE CHICAGO OFFICE WHO WILL ADVISE THEIR SHIPPER TO MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A REPRESENTATIVE TO RESPOND. DEVELOPED THE LADING WAS 55 GALLON DRUMS, WITH OPEN HEAD DRUMS AT THE LAST 4 ROWS NEAR THE DOORS. THERE WAS A SINGLE 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOORING TO PREVENT SIDE MOVEMENT OF THE LAST ROW OF OPEN HEAD DRUMS, AND A SINGLE 2X4 RUNNING SIDE TO SIDE OF THE CONTAINER, RESTING ON TOP OF THE LAST ROW OF OPEN HEAD DRUMS. THE DRUMS WERE NOT RISERED TO OFF SET FOR THE OVERSIZED CLOSURE RINGS, WHICH REQUIRED THE LAST DRUM IN EACH ROW TO BE OFF SET. AS THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT OF THE OPEN HEAD DRUMS, THE ENTIRE LOAD SHIFTED. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, ROUGHLY 1/3 OF THE WAY INTO THE CONTAINER, LOCATED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF AUTOMOTIVE PAINT, M6842-D, PERFORMANCE WHITE PRIMER, THAT WAS LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE DRUM HAD MOVED ACROSS AN ELEVATED FLOOR SCREW, WHICH DAMAGED THE BOTTOM CHIME, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE RESIDUE ON THE FLOORING WAS REMOVED, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE DAMAGED DRUM IS TO BE SHIPPED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST. NOTIFICATIONS WERE COMPLETED BY RMCC.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: WALTER GASTON PUT THIS DRUM ON THE PAIL OF THE TRLR W/OUT DUNNAGE. CHRISTIAN HIT THE DRUM WITH THE FORK LIFT BLADE THUS CAUSING A SPILL.

JOHN GROTHER, MANAGER INTERMODAL OPERATION, REPORTED PLACARDED CONTAINER APLS 303175 ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE. HE FURTHER ADVISED THAT A CONTRACTOR WAS WORKING A HOSTLER TURNING A LOAD OUT WHEN THE CONTAINER ROLLED OVER. THE CONTRACTOR WAS INJURED AND TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL. GEOFFREY REEDER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED. MGR REEDER REQUESTED CHEMTREC BE CONTACTED FOR INFORMATION REGARDING CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER. PATRICK WYCKO, REPRESENTATIVE WITH AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, ADVISED HE WOULD CALL BACK WITH INFORMATION REGARDING THE COMMODITY. MR. WYCKO ADVISED MGR. REEDER THAT THE DOW CHEMICAL PRODUCT WAS IN AN IBC PACKAGE AND THE MSDS WOULD BE AVAILABLE FROM DOW CHEMICAL. MR. REEDER ADVISED THAT THE TWENTY FOOT CONTAINER WAS NOT LEAKING AND WAS ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOSTLER TRACTOR AT A FORTY FIVE DEGREE ANGLE STILL ATTACHED BY THE FIFTH WHEEL. MR. WYCKO ADVISED THE DOOR OF THE CONTAINER SHOULD BE OPENED WITH A STRAP TO ASCERTAIN THE CONDITION OF THE PACKAGE. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE THE INJURED PARTY WAS USING A SPOTTING TRACTOR IN REVERSE TO PLACE THE CONTAINER. IT WAS UNKNOWN WHY THE CONTAINER ROLLED AS IT HAD NO VISABLE DAMAGE. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER WAS INFORMED THAT THE INJURED DRIVER WAS BUMPED AND BRUISED DURING THE ACCIDENT, BUT HE WAS NOT EXPOSED TO CHEMICALS. ONCE OTHER CONTAINERS WERE MOVED FROM THE AREA. REEDER REMOVED SEAL U.P. 4313653 AND PARTIALLY OPENED THE DOOR OF THIS CONTAINER. REEDER WAS ABLE TO SEE THAT THE CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING FROM  A VENT HOLE ON THEIR TOP. THE LIQUID WAS BEING CONTAINED INSIDE THE CONTAINER. CONTRACTOR QTS ROLLED THE CONTAINER UPRIGHT TO STOP THE LEAK, HOWEVER, THIS ALLOWED THE SPILLED MATERIAL TO RUN OUT THE DOOR. EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SITE TO COLLECT THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO A SAFE LOCATION WHERE THE BULK PACKAGES INSIDE WERE REMOVED AND CLEANED. THE INTERIOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS ALSO CLEANED. ALL THE PACKAGES WERE RETURNED TO DOW CHEMICAL FOR INSPECTION. THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR OTHER SHIPMENTS. DOW, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

TANKCAR GATX 79732 REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR. MR. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED FIVE OF SIX MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE AND ONE IN DOWN POSITION OFF THE COVER. CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC . RMCC MADE ALL OTHER NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.

column168: HARRY HOWARD, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED YARD PERSONNEL NOTICED AN ODOR FROM EMPTY TANKCARS GATX 94407, GATX 92965 AND NATX 33116 LOCATED IN YARD 1, TRACK 8, IN THE COFFEYVILLE YARD AND NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED. LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED JERRY COVEY, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD  OPERATIONS, WAS ASSIGNED THE INCIDENT. MGR. COVEY REPORTED FARMLAND HAD RESPONDED TO INSPECT THE TANKSCARS. FARMLAND PERSONNEL FOUND AN OPEN VAPOR VALVE ON TANKCAR GATX 92965. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE ODOR CEASED.

TANKCAR TILX 190003 RELEASED VAPORS ONLY DUE TO THREE OF FOUR BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AT CONNECTION BETWEEN LIQUID LINE AND CLOSURE (BLIND) FLANGE MR. LEO MARQUEZ, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZ MAT,  RESPONDED AND SECURED THE LOOSE BOLTS, INSPECTED THE CAR AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION WITH NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS. RMCC MADE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS AND THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED VIA CHEMTREC.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: RENAE, SECURITY GUARD, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF A FLAMMABLE SUBSTANCE WAS RELEASED FROM THE LEFT DOOR OF CONTAINER INBU 328868 CURRENTLY LOCATED AT THE ICTF YARD. DUFFY EXON. MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, RESPONDED AND REPORTED A DRIP OF BETWEEN 120-140 DROPS PER MINUTE AND REQUESTED CHEMTREC BE NOTIFIED TO VERIFY CONTENTS. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AT THE CUSTOM DOCK AREA AND TRANSLOADING SERVICES, A CONTRACTOR, WAS CONTRACTED TO PERFORM REMEDIATION. MIKE MURPHY, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, CSX INTERMODAL. LEANE MERIWEATHER. CSX HAZMAT, WAS CONFERRED WITH MGR. EXON TO DISCUSS THE STORAGE AND LEAKAGE DETAILS OF THE LOAD. THE BLOCKING AND BRACING IN THE CONTAINER FAILED AND THE LOAD SHIFTED, CAUSING DAMAGE TO 48 OF THE DRUMS. SIX OF THE DAMAGED DRUMS LEAKED.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: JOHN MILLER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED OF TANKCAR NATX 37756 LEAKING METHANOL FROM THE TOP MANWAY AT THE ALTON & SOUTHERN SWITCHING YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, IL. MR. MILLER WAS ALSO ADVISED BY STEVE AUGUSTINE, TRAINMASTER ALTON & SOUTHERN RAILWAY THAT HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, CONTRACTOR, WAS RESPONDING. RON SUTTON, HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INSPECTED THE CAR, FOUND A LOOSE LIQUID VALVE, RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR, TOOK THE LIQUID VALVE OFF, RESEALED IT AND REAPPLIED THE SEAL WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. MR. SUTTON ADVISED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE LOOKED AS THOUGH IT HAD BEEN REPAIRED RECENTLY. ON 6/9/02 MGR. MILLER RECEIVED MOVEMENT APPROVAL (FRA-0206131) AND CAR WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION. CAR ARRIVED AT TAYLOR, MICHIGAN 16:30 HOURS ON 6/18/02 WITH NO FURTHER COMPLICATIONS.

SECURITY OFFICER SMITH REPORTED CONTAINER MOLU 810525, LOCATED ON TRACK 807 IN THE ICTF YARD, DRIPPED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED AND THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED. DUFFY EXON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER EXON REPORTED THE PRODUCT, ORGANIC PEROXIDE, LEAKED AT A RATE OF TWENTY DROPS PER MINUTE FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE RIGHT SIDE OF TOP CONTAINER MOLU 810525, ONTO THE SIDE OF THE BOTTOM CONTAINER MOEU 010453 AND CREATED A TEN INCH DIAMETER POOL OF PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF STACK CAR DTTX 27354. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL, HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDING A CREW TO REMEDIATE THE LEAK. BOTH CONTAINERS WERE TRANSFERRED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE THEY COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. THE SHIPPER, ECOLAB, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ON THE SCENE AND RELIEVED MR. EXON. THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND THE LADING FOUND TO HAVE TOPPLED NEAR  THE CENTER OF THE LOAD. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON POLY PAILS, DOUBLE STACKED ON PALLETS FROM THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER TO THE CENTER PORTION OF THE CONTAINER. FROM THE CENTER FORWARD, THE PAILS WERE STACKED 3 HIGH PER PALLET. DID INFLATABLE BAGS HAD BEEN USED TO FILL THE CENTER VOIDS BETWEEN THE PALLETS. IT APPEARS THE PAILS STACKED 3 HIGH PER PALLET HAD SHIFTED DUE TO INADEQUATE SUPPORT OF THE DID BAGS, AND LOOSENING OF THE STRETCH WRAP, ALLOWING THE PAILS TO TOPPLE INTO THE VOIDS BETWEEN THE PALLETS. WHILE NONE OF THE PAILS ACTUALLY FAILED, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE VENTED BUNGS WHILE THE PAILS WERE AT AN ANGLE. THREE PALLETS, EACH CONTAINING 36 PAILS (108 TOTAL PAILS) RELEASED AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS TOTAL. THE PAILS WERE CLEANED, REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, AND HAND STACKED BACK ON TO PALLETS, THEN STRETCH WRAPPED. THE RESIDUE WAS CLEANED FROM THE CONTAINER, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. ONCE THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: DAN, TRAIN DISPATCHER 17, REPORTED TANKCAR HWPX 100 LOCATED ON TRACK TWO AT THE VAN BUREN YARD, 620 SOUTH 13TH STREET, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT. DAN STATED THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY BRIAN, CARMAN, WHO ADVISED THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A HEAVY RATE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE MIDDLE OF THE TANKCAR. DAN STATED THE VAN BUREN YARD HAS BEEN EVACUATED AND THERE WAS A DITCH CLOSE BY, HOWEVER THE PRODUCT WAS NOT MOVING TOWARD THE DITCH AT THIS TIME. JOHN STEWART, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. VAN BUREN FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE CONFERRING WITH RICHARD DOLE, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS. MR. DOLE INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND HE ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP NEAR THE A END OF THE TANKCAR, AT AN ESTIMATED RATE OF THREE TO FOUR GALLONS PER MINUTE. CHIEF HARRIS ADVISED A NEARBY PRODUCTION PLANT WAS BEING EVACUATED IN ADDITION TO THE YARD, FOR SAFETY REASONS. STATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE. MGR. STEWART REQUESTED NOTIFICATION AND RESPONSE BY CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, FOR AIR MONITORING PURPOSES. DOCTOR PHIL GOLD WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THAT AN AIR MONITOR TEAM WOULD BE ASSEMBLED AND MOBILIZED. EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. DOUG, SUPERVISOR FOR EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, REPORTED ONE BOLT WAS MISSING AND THREE BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, WHICH HE TIGHTENED TO STOP THE LEAK. AT 11:08 PM, RMCC CONTACTED CHIEF HARRIS LIFTED THE EVACUATION ORDER AND PERSONNEL FROM THE FOOD PROCESSING PLANT RETURNED TO WORK. ON 06/18/02 AT 12:25 AM, MGR STEWART REPORTED THREE TO FOUR HUNDRED GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND AND EVAPORATED. THE OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS CONTACTED AND ISSUED UPDATED INFORMATION ON THE INCIDENT. AT 7:39 AM, MGR. STEWART REINSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND REPLACED A MISSING BOLT ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE AND THEN BOLT TIGHTENED THE BOLT. THE TANKCAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S., WITH FLASH POINT ABOVE 37.8 C, AT OR ABOVE ITS FLASH POINT
column168: RICK EADES, DIRECTOR OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP MANWAY COVER OF TANKCAR CTNX 235017 WHEN THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED. MR. EADES STATED THE TANKCAR WAS CURRENTLY  LOCATED AT THE NORTH YARD. RMCAT, CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED  TO THE SCENE TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS. DON RHODES, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR CTNX 235017 WAS SET OUT AT THE OLD RIP TRACK #2 NEAR THE YARD OFFICE (901 W. 48TH AVENUE). RMCC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THROUGH JEFF AT CHEMTREC. MARK ROSS, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THAT RMCAT PERSONNEL PROPERLY TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS AND TANKCAR CTNX 235017 WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED RICK SAIDA, SURVEYOR FOR K LINE, INFORMED HIM OF A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE EAST YARD IN THE CITY OF COMMERCE, CA. DEAN RESPONDED AND FOUND CONTAINER KLTU 121241 TO BE LEAKING THROUGH THE LOWER BACK DOOR SEAL. MR. COOPER FURTHER STATED LESS THAN A PINT HAD LEAKED AND THE CAUSE WAS DETERMINED TO BE FROM A LOAD SHIFT. THREE  DRUMS WERE FOUND ON THEIR SIDE AND ONE UPSIDE DOWN. THE GROUND LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND REMOVED WITH ABSORBENT. DEVELOPED THE DRUMS WERE HELD IN PLACE WITH TY-GARD, WHICH APPEARD TO HAVE GIVEN WAY, ALLOWING THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS ON THE TOP TIER TO TOPPLE INTO THE VOID SPACE AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD. ONE OF THE DRUMS ON IT'S SIDE HAD THE BOTTOM CHIME DAMAGED FROM ANOTHER DRUM FALLING ONTO IT, ALLOWING THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, IDENTIFIED AS PEP SET 15110, A RESIN SOLUTION, MARKED AS FLAMMABLE. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECURMENT. EIGHT ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE NOTED WITH DAMAGE THAT DEEMED THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  THESE DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUEMENT. ONCE THE RESIDUE WAS CLEANED FROM THE CONTAINER, THE LADING WAS REWORKED AND PLACED BACK INTO THE SAME CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE OVER PACKED DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. WHILE BOTH THE TOP TIER AND FLOOR LOADED DRUMS HAD DUAL TY-GARD STRIPS TO RESTRAIN THE LOAD, IT APPEARS THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN OVER TIGHTENED DURING APPLICATION. THE FLOOR  LOADED DRUMS AT THE LAST ROW HAD EVIDENCE OF THE SIDES OF THE DRUMS BEING DEFORMED FROM THE TY-GARD BEING OVER TIGHTENED. PORTIONS OF THE FABRIC WERE HIGH SIDED ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS. THE DRUMS DID NOT MOVE AS A 2X4 HAD BEEN NAILED TO THE FLOOR AT THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS, INDICATING THE DAMAGED SIDES WERE CAUSED BY OVER TIGHTENING THE TY-GARD. WHEN THE TOP TIER TY-GARD LOSENED, IT DROPPED DOWN AS IT WAS NOT SECURED TO THE DRUMS WITH CORNER TAPE. ONCE THE MATERIAL DROPPED, THE DRUMS VIBRATED TO THE REAR AND FELL INTO THE VOID SPACE.  THE SIDE APPLICATION OF THE TY-GARD FOR THE TOP TIER ALSO SHOWED SIGNS OF BEING HIGH SCHOOL ON THE CORRUGATED SIDEWALLS.
