column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MIKE JONES, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR FPAX 931124, WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TOP AT THE ENGLEWOOD YARD IN HOUSTON, TX. GEOFFREY REEDER, ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED HIS ETA WAS ONE HOUR AND FIFTEEN MINUTES. REEDER ARRIVED ON SITE ABOUT 830PM. UPON INSPECTION, HE NOTICED THE CAR WAS DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. REEDER REMOVED SEAL "SEALED" 918524 FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. HE FOUND THE LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE. HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE. SEAL CTS 2103 WAS PLACED ON THE CAR. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

TUCSON YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 96773 WAS RELEASING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT TUCSON YARD, 1235 EAST CAMPBELL AVENUE, AND ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD ONE, TRACK 21, LINE TEN. THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ONE HUNDRED YARDS FROM THE TOWER AND NO CLOUD OF GAS WAS OBSERVED. YARD PERSONNEL HEARD THE TANKCAR RELEASING AS WELL AS DETECTING THE ODOR OF THE GAS. ALL PERSONNEL REMAINED UPWIND AND AWAY FROM THE TANKCAR. SAM LOPEZ, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, MOVED AND ISOLATED THE TANKCAR ON TRACK 804. INVESTIGATION OF THE TANK CAR REVEALED A TANK PRESSURE OF +260 PSI. DUE TO THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK, THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE VENTED TO REDUCE THE PRESSURE. SHIPPER MADE ARRANGMENTS TO REDUCE ONE TRUCK LOAD FROM THE CAR WHICH REDUCED THE PRESSURE. CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION AFTER THE LOAD REDUCTION. CAUSE OF PRESSURE BUILD UP APPEARS TO BE FROM CAR BEING OVERLOADED AT THE PLANT.

BILL WHALEY, TUCSON YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 72638 LOCATED ON TRACK 3 IN YARD 1. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS. DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT LESS THAN A HALF GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS ON THE GROUND WITH SOME PRODUCT ON THE TANK CAR. THE LEAK WAS AT THE LIQUID LINE GASKET. THE PRESSURE WAS RELEASED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. MR. JOHNSON REPORTED THE RUPTURE DISK WAS STILL INTACT AND PERSONNEL CLEANED THE CAR OF ALL STANDING PRODUCT AND MADE REPAIRS TO THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE WHICH APPEARED TO BE UNEVEN CAUSING THE ASSEMBLY NOT TO TIGHTEN PROPERLY.  REPAIRS CONSISTED OF APPLYING A THICKER GASKET WHICH ALLOWED THE FLANGE TO TIGHTEN PROPERLY. ON 06/29/2002, THE CAR WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE FREE OF LEAKS AND WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, OF A REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE HOFFMAN YARD IN SOUTH ST. PAUL, MN. GATX 98393 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. KEITH YUNGERBERG, MYO, ADVISED THAT THE YARD CREW HAD REPORTED THE LEAK AND SPILLAGE DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. MR. SEKAVEC REQUESTED HULCHER SERVICES RESPOND TO INSPECT AND PERFORM ANY NEEDED REPAIRS TO THE CAR ALONG WITH REMEDIATION OF THE INCIDENT AND ANY SPILLAGE. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED BY THE TRAIN CREW, INQUIRING ABOUT CHEMICAL PROPERTIES AND HAZARDS. HENDRYK SOWA WITH HULCHER ADVISED THAT ONE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVES ON THE CAR WAS DEFECTIVE IN THAT THE SPRING, SPRING RETAINER, AND NUTS WERE MISSING FROM THE VALVE OF THE DEVICE. PERSONNEL PLACED A TEMPORARY GAG ON THE VALVE TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPLASHING OF MATERIAL SHOULD THE CAR BE MOVED. THERE WAS A SECOND PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TO PREVENT FAILURE DUE TO BUILD UP OF EXCESS PRESSURE. THE CAR WAS ALSO CLEANED OF THE SPILLAGE AND THE MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH A SODA ASH SOLUTION TO PREVENT ANY HAZARDS DUE TO CONTACT WITH THE MATERIAL. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT (HAWKINS CHEMICAL-CHILD'S ROAD) ON SUNDAY, JULY 1, 2002, TO ALLOW THE CAR TO BE UNLOADED AND REPAIRS TO BE MADE TO THE VALVE.

LES MAKOVEC, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE TOP PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON TANK CAR GATX 98393. THE PRODUCT LEAKED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR AND WAS STARTING TO DRIP ON THE GROUND. THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD 8 ON TRACK 16 IN THE 18TH STREET YARD AND NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED. MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH HAZMAT RESPONSE, CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND. THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, APPARENTLY BECAUSE OF ROUGH HANDLING. THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAD RESEATED AND APPEARED TO BE OPERATING PROPERLY. THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASE FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: FILE: 2118 F & D, SHIPPER: TI GROUP AUTOMOTIVE SYSTEMS, AWB# XLA 17943174115 E9R. ON 06/20/2002 AT 04:07 AN ODOR OF GASOLINE WAS REPORTED AT DOOR C-38 OF BUILDING "C" AT OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL IT WAS RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN EUGENE LOVAS RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL TECHNICIAN LOVAS NOTED THAT THE AREA WAS AT FULL VOLUME OF FREIGHT AND CALLED FOR ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS KEVIN GAREN AND LORINE HARNER RESPONDED TO ASSIST. THE PART TIME TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND USING A PHOTO IONIZING DETECTOR BEGAN SEARCHING THROUGH THE FREIGHT UNTIL THE DETECTOR ALARM WENT OFF INDICATING THE ABOVE SHIPMENT AS THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS IN FACT EMITTING THE GASOLINE ODOR. THERE WERE SIX PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT BUT ONLY FIVE CONTAINER POLYETHYLENE PLASTIC TYPE AUTOMOTIVE GASOLINE TANKS. THERE WERE 2 EACH FUEL TANKS IN FOUR OF THE BOXES AND 1 IN THE FIFTH. THE BOXES WERE MAKE SHIFT BOXES HELD TOGETHER BY TNT SEOUL KOREA TAPE. ALSO NOTED WAS THAT THE TANKS WERE WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP. IN ADDITION TO THE TNT TAPE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING THERE WERE FRAGILE STICKERS BUT NOTHING TO INDICATE PROPER HANDLING SUCH AS ORIENTATION. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS NOTED UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE GASOLINE TANKS THAT NONE OF THE PORTS, VALVES OR HOSES HAD BEEN PLUGGED OR SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS TO PREVENT LEAKAGE. PRIOR TO PLACING THE FUEL TANKS INTO BAGS AND SALVAGE DRUMS IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT EACH HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 4 OUNCES OF GASOLINE EACH. IT IS UNKNOWN HOW MUCH GASOLINE WAS IN EACH TANK PRIOR TO OFFERING THE SHIPMENT FOR TRANSPORT. THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED INTO THREE UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUMS SINCE THEY COULD ONLY ACCOMMODATE TWO OF THE GASOLINE TANKS EACH. NOTE: THE SIXTH PACKAGE: ONLY CONTAINED PARTS, SUCH AS STRAPS, VALVES, AND FASTENERS. CLEAR OF SCENE:04:28

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: JOHNNY ARRIVED AT THE WELLS DRAW PLANT ON THE MORNING OF 6-22-02. HE PULLED ONTO THE OFF LOADING RACK, HOOKED THE SHORTER OF THE TWO HOSES TO THE OUTLET AT THE REAR OF TRAILER #357. HE THEN HOOKED UP THE VAPOR HOSE, OPENED HIS VALVES, STARTED INTERLINES PUMP AND BEGAN UNLOADING. WHEN TRAILER #357 WAS UNLOADED TO AROUND 50% THE TRAILER STOPPED UNLOADING. THE PLANT OPERATOR TOLD JOHNNY THAT BECAUSE OF THE VAPOR PRESSURES OF THIS PRODUCT,  HE WOULD HAVE TO USE HIS PUMP TO PUSH THE PRODUCT TO THE PLANT PUMP TO FINISH UNLOADING. AT THE START OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS OF TRAILER #357, THE VAPOR PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER WAS AROUND 200 PSI. AT THE TIME JOHNNY HAD TO HOOK UP TO THE TRAILER PUMP TO FINISH UNLOADING THE VAPOR PRESSURE HAD DROPPED TO ABOUT 160 PSI.  JOHNNY HOOKED UP THE SECOND HOSE ON THE RACK (THE LONGER OF THE TWO AND THE HOSE THAT FAILED ON THE  SECOND LOAD) TO HIS TRAILER PUMP OUTLET, CLOSED THE OUTLET AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, OPENED THE PUMP OUTLET ENGAGED THE TRAILER PUMP AND BEGAN UNLOADING.  WHILE JOHNNY  WAS UNLOADING AN INTERLINE OWNED TRUCK PULLED ALONG SIDE HIM, HOOKED UP TO THE PRESSURE BLOW DOWN HOSE (LOCATED ON THE SAME RACK AS THE  DISCHARGE HOSES BEING USED BY JOHNNY) AND PRESSURED DOWN HIS TRAILER (LPG), THEN PULLED OUT AND TO THE SCALES. JOHNNY FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT INCIDENT, UNHOOKED THE LIQUID HOSE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, UNHOOKED THE LIQUID HOSE AT THE TRAILER"S PUMP, UNHOOKED THE VAPOR LINE AND PULLED AWAY FROM THE RACK-MADE A U-TURN AND PARKED HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND ABOUT 70 FEET FROM THE UNLOADING RACK. ALEX, IN TRUCK NUMBER 296, PULLING TRAILER NUMBER 524 BACKED INTO POSITION TO BEGIN UNLOADING AT THE RACK AND BEGAN TO HOOK UP TO THE LIQUID OUTLET AT THE REAR OF UNIT #524. JOHNNY LEFT HIS TRUCK, WALKED ACROSS  THE DRIVEWAY AND TOLD ALEX HE WOULD NEED TO USE HIS PUMP TO UNLOAD SO ALEX TOOK THE SHORTER OF THE TWO LIQUID HOSES AT THE RACK AND HOOKED IT TO THE LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER 524'S PUMP DISCHARGE. HE ALSO HANDED JOHNNY THE LONGER OF THE TWO HOSES (THE HOSE THAT FAILED) UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER. JOHNNY HOOKED THAT HOSE TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF TRAILER 534'S PUMP DISCHARGE AND OPENED THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THE GATE VALVES ON THE TRAILER AND SLOWLY OPENED THE VALVES ON THE END OF THE HOSES. ALEX HAD WALKED OVER TO INTERLINE'S PUMP AND PUSHED THE START BUTTON. AT THAT TIME, THE COUPLING THAT JOHNNY HOOKED UP FAILED AND THE HOSE BLEW OFF, HITTING JOHNNY ON THE ARM AND ALLOWING LIQUID FROM THE PUMP PIPING AND THE HOSES TO ESCAPE TO ATMOSPHERE.  THE HOSE WHIPPED AROUND AND BACK UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER, THE HOSE ON THE LEFT SIDE REMAINED HOOKED. THE LIQUID GAS SPEWED THROUGH THE PUMP PIPING, CONTAMINATING JOHNNY'S CLOTHING, AND SHOT ACROSS THE DRIVEWAY TO JOHNNY'S PARKED TRUCK #245 AND AT SOME POINT IGNITED, CATCHING UNIT 245 ON FIRE. JOHNNY WAS PICKING HIMSELF UP AFTER HAVING BEEN KNOCKED DOWN BY THE HOSE AND ESCAPING PRODUCT WHEN THE FIRE BALL ERUPTED. HE WAS ABLE TO RUN BEHIND UNI
A PALLET OF FREIGHT FELL ONTO PALLET OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DURING UNLOADING AT TERMINAL DOCK.  PACIFIC TREATMENT INC. CLEANED UP SPILL AND WILL HANDLE DISPOSAL.  DISPOSAL HAS NOT YET TAKEN PLACE.

column168: FILE:3116-D, SHIPPER:COSTCO WHOLESALE, AWB# EDS 74753402570 ONT.  ON 08/25/2002 AT 14:46, A CALL CAME IN REPORTING  THAT THERE WAS  A PACKAGE THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR OF GASOLINE, BUT NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE THE CALLER DESCRIBED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION AS A KARCHER 2400 PSI PRESSURE WASHER "GAS POWERED". PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DIANE RAMSDEN AND CECELIA HICKEY RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION DOOR A-2 BUILDING "A" LOCATED AT OUR SPORT HUB FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL IT WAS RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS UPON ARRIVAL DONNED THEIR PERSONAL AND BEGAN LOOKING AT THE OUTER MOST PACKAGING FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE NONE WERE FOUND. THE PACKAGE WAS THE MANUFACTURES RE-PRINTED PICTORIAL PICTURES AND INFORMATION OF THE PRESSURE WASHER.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE AND DID IN FACT OBSERVE A PRESSURE WASHER MACHINE AND THAT THERE WERE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE OF FUEL COMING FROM THE GASOLINE TANK WHICH WAS PART OF THE UNIT. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT THEN OVERPACKED THE SHIPMENT INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITIES SECURITY CAGE FOR SHIPPER'S DISPOSITION.  NOTE: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT OUR SORT HUB FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177 VIA COMMON TRUCK CARRIER AND WAS DESTINED FOR COMMON TRUCK CARRIER TO THE WEST COAST. CLEAR OF SCENE 15:04

0300 RECEIVED CALL OF LEAKING TANK CAR FROM KENNY SCONZA W/GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (GES) I AM TO REPORT TO SCENE WHILE CREW PICKS UP HAZMAT TRAILER. 0330 ON SCENE AND REPORT TO JOE BERTUCCI WITH NOPBRR WE PROCEED TO LEAKING RAILCAR TO ASSESS THE CONDITION OF CAR AND TO DEVELOP A PLAN OF ACTION.  0345 MEET WITH NOFD HAZMAT  TEAM TO EXPLAIN WHAT CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WILL BE TAKEN BY GES. THEY INFORM ME THAT STATE POLICE AND LADEQ WILL NOT BE ON SITE AND THAT AFTER OUR INSPECTION THEY WILL ALSO DEPART.  0400 HAZMAT TRAILER ARRIVES SAMMY JONES DRESSES OUT IN LEVEL "C" PPE AND WE PROCEED TO RAIL CAR TO INSPECT AND TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING. USING 4-GAS METER (02,LEL,H2S,CO) NO LEAKING OF VAPOR COULD BE DETECTED. 0420 NOFD DEPARTS SITE. 0440 USING A PID TO MEASURE  ORGANIC VAPOR THE AREA AROUND SRV AND UNDER DOME WERE  CHECKED WITH NO DETECTABLE READINGS ABOVE BACKGROUND. WE DECIDE TO INSTALL PRESSURE GAGE TO INSURE PRODUCT IS NOT REACTING AND RELEASING PRESSURE FROM SRV.  0500 PRESSURE GAUGE INSTALLED AND SHOWS 4 PSI, SRV IS SET FOR 75 PSI. PID IS USED TO CHECK FOR LEAKS. A READING IN EXCESS OF 1700 PPM WAS DISCOVERED ALONG A 6"  AREA WERE THE HATCH GASKET CONTACTS GASKET SEAL.  HATCH WAS TIGHTENED USING STANDARD PROCEDURES. CHECKED AGAIN TO FIND READINGS @750 PPM.  0550 IT IS DETERMINED THAT PRESSURE WILL HAVE TO BE RELEASED AND GASKET CHANGED IN ORDER TO COMPLETELY STOP VAPOR RELEASE. PID READINGS ALONG TRACKS DOWNWIND OF CAR WERE LESS THAN 7 PPM AND OPPM AT A DISTANCE OF 15 TO 20'.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE CAR WAS LESS THAN 100' FROM HOMES WE NEEDED TO DECIDE WERE THE SAFEST PLACE TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE AND CHANGE GASKET.  0640 THE CAR WILL BE MOVED TO RAIL SPUR BELONGING TO CSX RAILROAD.  THIS SPUR IS EQUIPPED AND DESIGNED FOR THIS PURPOSE.  0730 RETURNED TO GES SHOP AND OFF CLOCK TO AWAIT ARRIVAL OF CAR TO CSX.  800 PUT 2 MORE GES PERSONNEL ON STAND BY. SCBA'S WILL BE USED ONCE HATCH IS OPENED TO REMOVE AND REPLACE GASKET. SAFETY REQUIRES 4 PERSONNEL TO BE ON SITE WHILE UNDER AIR.  0900 ON SITE CSX START SETTING UP EQUIPMENT. 1) 55 GALLON DRUM OF SODIUM BICARB TO BE USED TO SCRUB VAPORS. 2) 2" CHEMICAL HOSE AS VAPOR LINE 3)  PRESSURE GAGE WITH AIR FITTING TO PRESSURE CAR BACK TO 4 LB. 4) 11.8 CFM COMPRESSOR 5) PPE AND TOOLS REQUIRED TO COMPLETE TASK  0945 CAR ARRIVES ON TRACK BRIEFING AND TAILGATE SAFETY MEETING CONDUCTED.  0955 ENTRY IS MADE TO INSTALL VAPOR LINE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE. AIR MONITORING CONDUCTED 500 PPM READING AT TOP OF DRUM WITH READINGS <5PPM 10' DOWN WIND AND O PPM 20' DOWN WIND. 1040 PRESSURE DOWN TO 0 PSI. USING LEVEL "B" PPE HATCH IS OPENED AND GASKET REMOVED. UPON INSPECTION OF OLD GASKET THERE WERE NO OBVIOUS DEFECTS NOTICED TO AS TO WHY IT WAS LEAKING.  1200 SECOND ENTRY MADE TO INSTALL NEW GASKET. 1230 NEW GASKET-INSTALLED HATCH TIGHTENED USING AN 11.8 CFM COMPRESSOR PRESSURE IS BROUGHT TO 2.5 PSI. HATCH IS CHECKED WITH PID 1700 PPM AROUND HATCH. HATCH IS TIGHTENED ANOTHER TURN AT EACH BOLT AND READINGS DROP TO LES

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON TRAILER # 313-6878.  WHEN WE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR WE IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THE SMELL AND PAINT, AND NOTICED THE PRESENCE OF A LIQUID UNDER THE TOTE.  THERE WAS ALSO VISIBLE EVIDENCE OF THE PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE AND FRONT OF THE METAL TOTE.  THE FIRST OBSERVATION WAS THAT OF THE GASKET ON A BUNG BEING TWISTED AND SEEMED TO BE DEFECTIVE WITH A LARGE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AROUND THE BUNG LID.  WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED BASF, AND THEY PROVIDED ASSISTANCE BY SENDING ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC.  TIM VERNON AND JASON EGELSTON ARRIVED ON SCENE.  THEY CLEANED UP THE TOTE, REPLACED THE GASKET, AND BUNG LID, TESTED THE NEW FITTING AND DISPOSED OF ALL CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD AND CLEANING MATERIAL. IT WAS ALSO NOTED, THAT THE PRODUCT WAS IN THE TOP OF THE BUNG LID AND ON THE CORNERS.  THIS SEEMED TO INDICATE THAT THE PRODUCT MIGHT HAVE BEEN PLACED THERE DURING FILLING, OR BY PLACING ANOTHER TOTE ON TOP OF THIS ONE (THIS TYPE OF TOTE IS DESIGNED TO BE STACKED IN A WAREHOUSE).
WHILE DELIVERING, A SMALL OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: ON 06/28/2002 AT 01:13 A CALL CAME IN THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING ON A SORT BELT AND THE BELT WAS DOWN IN BUILDING "C" AT DOOR "C-10" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME BETH PARKER RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL TECHNICIAN PARKER FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING. TECHNICIAN PARKER PH'D THE CLEAR LIQUID AND THE PH READING WAS NEUTRAL. TECHNICIAN PARKER THEN PLACED THE BOX INTO DOUBLE BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND OPENED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION. ONCE THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OPENED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER WHITE PLASTIC DRUM WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS STATED ABOVE AND HAD A BILL OF LADING/MANIFEST ATTACHED THAT CONFIRMED THE MARKINGS AND LABEL ON THE WHITE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY WHERE IT WAS FURTHER INVESTIGATED. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN EUGENE LOVAS AND TERRY RUGGERRIE DONNED SCBA'S (SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS) AND LEVEL "B" CHEMICAL SUITES FOR MAXIMUM PROTECTION SINCE THE MANIFEST INDICATED "MERCURY". THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PLASTIC DRUM AND FOUND 18 ORANGE BIOHAZARD BAGS THAT CONTAINED CLEAR PLASTIC VIALS THAT HAD A MUDDY WATER WITH BEADS OF MERCURY. THESE BAGS WERE TIED AND THE VIALS WERE SEALED. THEY FURTHER DISCOVERED 15 ORANGE BIOHAZARD BAGS THAT WERE IDENTICAL TO THE OTHERS BUT THE BAGS HAD NOT BEEN TIED AND THE CLOSURES ON THE VIALS WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEAN WHICH WAS THE REASON THERE WAS LEAKAGE. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALAVGE DRUM AND PUT INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING TSA INVESTIGATION. CLEAR OF SCENE: 01:42.

column168: ON JUNE 24, 2002 I LOADED (2) ROLLOFF BOXES AT 21ST CENTURY EMI IN FERNLEY, NV GOING TO US ECOLOGY BEATTY, NV. LOADING: I ARRIVED 21ST CENTURY EMI AND DID MY WALKED AROUND THE BOXES TO MAKE SURE ALL DOGS ARE ON THE DOORS AND TARPS ARE SECURE. A VISUAL INSPECTION SHOWED BOTH BOXES WERE IN PROPER ODOR. AFTER INSPECTING THE BOXES I LOADED THEM AND WHILE SECURING THEM I DO A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM. TRANSPORT: I LEFT FERNLEY AND PROCEEDED TO BEATTY. I MADE IT TO FALLON WHEN I HAD TO STOP AND PUT STRAPS OVER THE TARPS OF THE FRONT BOX. TH CROSS WIND WAS MORE THAN THE BUNGEE CORDS COULD HANDLE. ALL IS SECURE, BUMP TIRES AND DO A VISUAL CHECK. I THEN PROCEEDED TO BEATTY DOING ALL  MY NORMAL CHECKS ALONG THE WAY. I ARRIVED AT BEATTY, WENT INTO THE BURRO INN, ATE DINNER, WENT BACK OUT TO THE TRUCK, DID ANOTHER WALK AROUND AND THEN WENT TO BED. TUESDAY JUNE 25 AT 0500 HOURS I GOT UP AND WALK AROUND THE TRUCK AND FOUND MY FRONT BOX WAS DRIPPING FROM BEHIND ONE OF THE UPRIGHT SUPPORT POST. I IMMEDIATELY DROVE TO US ECOLOGY 10 MILES AWAY WERE I GRABED SOME HELP TO CONTAIN THE LEAK, US ECOLOGY HAD ME UNLOAD THE BOX WITHIN MINUTES. AFTER UNLOADING, MS LAURIE SANDERS IN REGULATORY AND COMPLIANCE AND I RETURN TO THE BURRO INN TO ASSESS THE SPILL AREA. I THEN STARTED TO CALL ALL THE PROPER AUTHORITY. NYE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND THE DISPATCHER SAID SHE WOULD NOTIFY THE NHP, THEN I CALLED NYE COUNTY EMERGENCY SERVICES AND SPOKE WITH STEVE MAISON, I EXPLAIN WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND HE SAID HE WOULD BE RIGHT OUT. AFTER TALKING WITH MR. MAISON I CALLED N.D.E.P. CARSON CITY AND MADE A REPORT TO THEM. I THEN CALLED THE GENERATOR AND GAVE THEM THE BAD NEWS AT WHICH TIME THEY MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A HAZ-MAT CREW TO COME OUT AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND REPORTED KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WOULD HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  MR. WELCH WAS UPDATED AND REPORTED HE CONTACTED SINCLAIR, CONSIGNEE, WHO REPORTED THEY WOULD SEND A TRUCK TO OFF-LOAD SOME PRODUCT.  MGR. KEELING ADVISED THAT A REPRESENTATIVE OF RM CAT, CONTRACTOR, WOULD RESPOND TO SUPERVISE TRANSLOADING.  MANAGER KEELING FURTHER ADVISED THAT 1800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED BY SINCLAIR. CONTRACTOR, RM CAT DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE.  CONSIGNEE HAD ALREADY SECURED THE TANK CAR.

RICH VAUGHN, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR NATX 78347, NOT ENTRAINED AND LOCATED IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK CLASSIFICATION YARD AT THE NORTH END OF BOWL 51.  JOHN STEWART, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED.  MGR. VAUGHN REPORTED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY NINETY-SIX DROPS EVERY THIRTY SECONDS OR A QUART EVERY TEN TO FIFTEEN MINUTES FROM ONE VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR. MR. VAUGHN WAS CONFERRED WITH JOHN STEWART, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS.  MGR. STEWART RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  LESS THAN FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND THERE WAS NO SOIL CONTAMINATION AS THE CHEMICAL EVAPORATES READILY.  MR. STEWART STATED THE LEAK WAS FROM THE MOST "B" END AT A HEATER DRAIN COIL.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND SHIPPER CONSULTED.  FRA ISSUED AN EXEMPTION TO MOVE THE CAR AS IS ON JUNE 26, 2002, FRA 0206144.  NONA, NORTH LITTLE ROCK FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  SHANNON, ARKANSAS EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

JOHN STEWART, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, BE NOTIFIED.  MGR. SIMPSON RESPONDED, INSPECTED THE TANKCAR, AND DETERMINE THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED. MR. SIMPSON REPLACED THE DISK IN KIND.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SB ON I-55 HEADING TO A SHELL STATION AT 1-55 & ROUTE 53. DRIVER WAS IN THE FAR RIGHT LANE STARTED TO SLOW BECAUSE OF TRAFFIC BACKING UP DUE TO CONSTRUCTION AND CONGESTION AT THE EXIT TO RT. 53. BEING FAMILIAR WITH AREA DRIVER HAD HIS FOUR-WAY WARNING FLASHERS ON. AS HE CONTINUED TO SLOW TO 40 MPH HE WAS HIT FROM BEHIND BY ANOTHER SEMI(OWNED AND OPERATED BY SHENANDOAH MOTOR EXPRESS INC. OUT OF VERSAILLES, OH). OUR UNIT MOVED TO THE SHOULDER WHILE THE OTHER VEHICLE (SHENANDOAH) CONTINUED TO BOUNCE OFF OTHER VEHICLES (4-PASSENGER CARS AND 3 TRUCKS TOTAL).  OUR CARGO TANK T-4407 DEVELOPED A LEAK AS A RESULT OF BEING HIT IN THE REAR (9 O'CLOCK POSITIONS). DRIVER BILL Jr. USED ABSORBENT SOCKS AND SAND BAGS (FROM ROAD CONSTRUCTION) TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL GASOHOL. INTERSTATE 55 WAS SHUT DOWN BY THE POLICE/FIRE DEPARTMENTS DURING THE PROCESS. WE SENT OUT ANOTHER TANKER TO REMOVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE FOURTH COMPARTMENT. WE ESTIMATED LESS THEN 19-GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANKER. MOST OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT EVAPORATED BY THE HIGH WINDS AND SUN.  WE CONTACTED SET ENVIRONMENTAL, INC TO COME IN AND REMOVE ABOUT 5 DRUMS OF POSSIBLE CONTAMINATED EARTH FROM THE SCENE. AFTER THE TRANSFER FROM THE LEAKING UNIT WE DELIVERED THE REMAINING PRODUCT TO THE SHELL SERVICE STATION. DAMAGED UNIT WAS DRIVEN BACK TO THE TERMINAL. DRUMS OF EARTH ARE BEING TEST TO DETERMINE PROPER DISPOSAL.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE BOX WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SPILLAGE EVAPORATED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

AT 1026 HRS ON 6-8-02, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED BY THE RMCC TANK CAR UTLX99309, LOCATED IN TRACK 304, SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX. WAS LEAKING. CHECK OF WAYBILL INFORMATION INDICATED CAR WAS LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA,  UN1005. IMMEDIATE RESPONSE AND INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED A MINOR RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THE THREADS OF THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP. AFTER SEVERAL UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPTS IN TIGHTENING THE CAP, MGR LERCH APPLIED A "MIDLAND" CAPPING KIT OVER THE THERMOMETER WELL ASSEMBLY WHICH STOPPED PRODUCT RELEASE. AFTER SECURING THE CAR MGR, LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CONTINENTAL NITROGEN RESOURCES; ROSEMONT,MN AND SPOKE TO MR DAVID BEDNAR, COMPANY PRESIDENT. UPON ADVISING MR BEDNAR OF THE RELEASE, HE INDICATED THAT THE CAR WAS SHIPPED IN THEIR NAME, AND LOADED OUT OF NECHES INDUSTRIAL PARK; BEAUMONT, TX. MR BEDNAR THEN REFERRED MGR LERCH TO DEAN DRENT, TRANSPORTATION & DISTRIBUTION COORDINATOR, CONTINENTAL NITROGEN FOR FURTHER ASSISTANCE. UPON ADVISING MR DRENT OF THE RELEASE, IT WAS INITIALLY DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE TRANSLOADED AND SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS. AFTER FURTHER DISCUSSION AND REVIEW IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SHIPPED BACK TO NECHES INDUSTRIAL PARK FOR UNLOADING, AND SHOPPED FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS. MR DRENT APPLIED FOR, AND WAS GRANTED AND FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL # FRA-0206130 ON 6-11-02. ON 6-19-02 CAR DEPARTED HOUSTON WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

AT 0242 HRS ON 6-9-02, CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED BY THE RMCC THAT TANK CAR GATX 13201, LOCATED ON TRACK 317, SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX., WAS LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION OF CAR, THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS NOTED TO BE MISSING. MGR LERCH REPLACED THE GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WHICH SECURED THE CAR. AFTER SECURING THE CAR, MGR LERCH HAD THE CAR SET OUT FOR FURTHER HANDLING. ON 6-10-02, CTS MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, KMTEX , AND SPOKE TO THE PLANT MANAGER DAVID SPACEK. UPON ADVISING MR SPACEK OF THE RELEASE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SIDES OF THE CAR REQUIRED NEUTRALIZING. ON 6-11-02 HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED THE SIDES OF THE CAR. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: AT 1320HRS ON 6-9-02, FRANK LERCH MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED A LOCAL TRAIN CREW HAD REPORTED TO ORSON ROBERTS MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF CAR UTLX 661385. THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN VELASCO YARD 2, TRACK 100; FREEPORT, TX UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MANAGER LERCH, CONTACTED MR ROBERTS AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER, DOW CHEMICAL LOCATED IN FREEPORT, HAD BEEN CONTACTED , RESPONDED, SECURED AND CLEANED THE SIDES OF THE CAR. AT 1340HRS, MGR LERCH SPOKE WITH BILL YATES, ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONDER WITH DOW CHEMICAL (979-235-7620). HE INDICATED THAT THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS IN PLACE BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT, WHICH ALLOWED RESIDUE PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE SIDES OF THE CAR. MR YATES FURTHER INDICATED AFTER COMPLETING ALL CORRECTIVE ACTIONS, THAT THE CAR WOULD BE RE-INSPECTED UPON ARRIVAL AT THEIR FREEPORT FACILITY. AFTER THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED, IT WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AND NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

AT 0802HRS ON 6-27-02, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC AND ADVISED THAT SWITCHMAN C.W. REDDEN HAD COMPLAINED TO MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS JAY EVERETT OF HIS NOSE BURNING FROM A STRONG ODOR IN THE AREA OF TRACK 205, YARD 2, BEAUMONT, TX A REVIEW OF TRACK LISTS INDICATED SEVERAL CARS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IN TRACK 205. UPON RECEIVING THE COMPLAINT, MR EVERETT STATED MR REDDEN WAS TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY, EXAMINED AND PROVIDED WITH A BLOOD GAS TEST WHICH TESTED NEGATIVE FOR EXPOSURE AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED. ON ARRIVAL AT THE BEAUMONT YARD, MGR LERCH INSPECTED TANK CARS IN TRACK 205, NOTING A SLIGHT PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON TANK CAR GATX 92692; WHICH GAUGED AT APPROXIMATELY 90 PSI. AFTER LOCATING LEAKING CAR, MGR LERCH HAD CAR SET-OUT/ISOLATED FOR SAFETY PURPOSES AND REPAIR. AFTER CAR WAS ISOLATED. MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES AND SPOKE TO JACK CURRY, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR, ADVISING HIM OF THE CAR'S CONDITION. MR CURRY INDICATED THE CAR WAS SHIPPED BY FARMLAND AND LOADED OUT OF NEUCHES INDUSTRIAL PARK,BEAUMONT TX. MGR LERCH CONTACTED FACILITIES MANAGER OF NECHES INDUSTRIAL PARK, BILL CASTLEMAN, WHO IN TURN RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WITH SEVERAL FACILITIES PERSONNEL. AFTER INSPECTION OF CAR BY MR CASTLEMAN, HE DISPATCHED RESCAR MOBIL-RAIL CAR REPAIR TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. ON ARRIVAL OF RESCAR PERSONNEL, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE O -RING WERE FOUND TO BE WORN AND WERE REPLACED, STOPPING THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. CAR WAS FURTHER INSPECTED WITH NO ADDITIONAL EXCEPTIONS NOTED. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

AT 0525HRS ON 6-28-02, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT SCOTT VAN WOERK. MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR DNAX 125017 WAS LEAKING DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 4, BASIN YARD HOUSTON, TX. IMMEDIATE RESPONSE AND INSPECTION OF CAR BY MGR LERCH REVEALED LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED ONTO THE SIDES OF THE CAR, AND HAD EVAPORATED, WITH NO IMPACT TO THE GROUND. ONE FOURTH OF THE MANWAY GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE MISSING ON THE HINGED SIDE OF THE MANWAY COVER, THE REMAINING GASKET WAS NOTED TO BE IN POOR CONDITION. AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, AND SPOKE TO MARK LEHL, DIRECTOR OF OPERATIONS, OCTEL STARREON. UPON EXPLAINING TO MR LEHL THE CONDITION OF THE CAR, HE DISPATCHED RESCAR MOBIL RAIL CAR REPAIR TO EFFECT NECESSARY REPAIRS. ON ARRIVAL OF RESCAR MOBIL REPAIR, IT WAS FOUND THAT RESCAR DID NOT HAVE THE CORRECT SIZE MAN WAY GASKET, AND THAT A GASKET WOULD HAVE TO BE CUT. AT APPROXIMATELY 1500HRS, RESCAR RETURNED, REPLACED THE GASKET, CLOSED AND TIGHTENED THE MAN WAY COVER SWING BOLTS WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING  FROM THIS INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: EFFINGHAM EQUITY SOLD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO JAMES & CHARLES ECKERT FOR AGRUUCLUTRAL USE. A FARM HAND, CHAD LOWE PICKED UP THE TWO TANKS (1150 GALLON EACH) OF AMMONIA FROM OUR ROBINSON, ILLINOIS FACILITY. CHAD WAS PULLING THE TANKS NORTH ON ILLINOIS ROUTE 1, HE RAN OFF OF THE EAST SIDE OF THE ROAD. LOST CONTROL, AND TRAVELED DOWN THE DITCH, STRIKING SEVERAL SMALL TREES. THE TRUCK FLIPPED OVER ONTO ITS TOP, THE TANKS DID THE SAME. THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPENED ON THE SECOND NURSE TANK DURING THE OVERTURN. 3440 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE HUTSONVILLE AND ROBIN FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED, AS WELL AS THE CRAWFORD COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT ILLINOIS ROUTE 1 WAS CLOSED FOR NEARLY 3 HOURS. TO PREVENT THIS THE ECKERTS SHOULD PROVIDE THEIR EMPLOYEES WITH TRAINING ON HOW TO TRANSPORT ANHYDROUS AMMONIA SAFELY.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: FILE:3259 D, SHIPPER: EI DUPONT DE NEMOURS, AWB# 6618033144 BRU ON 6/18/02 AT 1445 DAVID PISHOCK/PM SUPERVISOR CALLED TO REPORT A LIQUID SPILL WITH AN ODOR AT OUR OUTBASE STATION LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC. AIRPORT BUSINESS CENTER 205 DIPLOMAT DRIVER LESTER, PA 19113 VIA OUR HAZMAT HOTLINE/(866) 588-2002. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR MATTHEW GROSVENOR CONTACTED H.M.H.T.T.C RESPONSE TEAM INC. IN PARSIPPANY, NJ VIA TELEPHONE/(973) 335-6696 TO RESPOND. MATTHEW ALSO CONTACTED CINDY THOMPSON AT DUPONT TO OBTAIN A M.S.D.S. FOR THIS PRODUCT AND CINDY CONSEQUENTLY CALLED PETRO CLEAN TO ASSIST IN THE MITIGATION OF THIS SPILL. AFTER ARRIVING AND DONNING PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THE CONTRACTED RESPONSE TEAMS FOUND THREE INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS, EACH WITH A DRAIN SPOUT ON THE BOTTOM ATTACHED TO A SKID. THESE THREE IBC'S WERE IN THE BACK OF A SEMI TRAILER. ONLY ONE OF THESE IBC'S WAS LEAKING FROM THE VALVE ON THE BOTTOM. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS IBC TO BE LEAKING "FLUOROPOLYMER RESIN". IT IS UNKNOWN IF THE CLOSURE ON THIS IBC WAS SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. WHILE TRYING TO REPOSITION THE IBC IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AN AIRBORNE EMPLOYEE STRUCK THE VALVE WITH A FORKLIFT CAUSING THE IBC TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS. A REPORT WAS FILED WITH CHEMTREC: 06182002085 WHEN JERRY MULVILLE INITIALLY REPORTED THIS SPILL TO THE DOT VIA TELEPHONE HE ASSUMED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. AFTER RECEIVING AND INVESTIGATION THE M.S.D. FROM DUPONT THIS PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED TO NOT BE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE EPA, DELAWARE COUNTY EMERGENCY HAZMAT TEAM AND THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE WERE REPORTER TO BE SATISFIED WITH THE CONTRACTED RESPONSE TEAM'S CLEAN UP PROCEDURES FOR THIS SPILL. ALL MATERIALS USED TO MITIGATE THIS SPILL WERE PACKED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND TAKEN TO A WASTE COMPANY BY H.M.H.T.T.C. FOR DISPOSAL. THE EMPTY TOTE WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

FILE: 3257 D, SHIPPER: ACROS ORGANICS, AWB368560901662 EPT. ON 6/14/02 AT 0820 A LIQUID SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT OUR OUTBASE STATION ABX AIR, INC. 6805 PARKE EAST BOULEVARD TAMPA, FL 33610 VIA OUR HAZMAT HOTLINE / (866) 588-2002. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR BENJAMIN TAYLOR CONTACTED AMERICAN COMPLIANCE TECHNOLOGIES, INC. (ACT) IN APOLLO BEACH, FL VIA TELEPHONE/ (863) 533-2000 TO RESPOND. AFTER ARRIVING AND DONNING PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THEY FOUND FOUR FIBERBOARD BOXES WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING. THEY REMOVED THESE SHIPMENTS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THESE FOUR BOXES TO EACH CONTAIN A 1 X 4 L GLASS BOTTLE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "CHLOROFORM 99% HPLC, 6.1, UN1888, PG III" THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLE WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN, LEAKING ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 4 L. THE REMAINING THREE PIECES WERE LEAKED ON (ONLY) BY THE LEAKING SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND HAD A CORRECT SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO DECLARE THE CONTENTS AS REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. ALL FOUR PIECES OF THIS SHIPMENT WERE RESEALED, PLACED INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. ACT RESPONSE TEAM DECLARE AREA CLEAR AND ALLOW ABX PERSONNEL TO RETURN TO THEIR WORK AREAS: 1244 ACT RESPONSE TEAM CLEAR OF SCENE 1555

UPON DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE TWO PAILS WERE FOUND LEAKING FROM THE BUNG CAPS.  THE BUNG CAPS WERE LEAKING DUE TO THE CRIMPING RINGS NOT SEATING PROPERLY ON THE LID OF THE DRUM.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE PAIL AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

DRIVER DID NOT UNHOOK HOSE FROM TANK AND A FITTING ON THE TANK BROKE IN A TURN.  CSX CALLED OUT HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEANUP.  THE LEAD MAN MIKE POWERS WAS ON SITE FOR 13 HRS AND THEY REMOVED 3 TRUCK LOADS OF STONE AND DIRT AND WILL REPLACE THE STONE ON MON 6/24 WITH NEW AND HAUL OUT THE OLD BY 6/25, LARRY WALSH CSX DOCK SUPERINTENDENT WAS NOTIFIED.
